<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of Afghans went to the polls Tuesday on the first day of general elections that will be held over 10 days, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> reported. They are the first general elections in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> since pro-Soviet military officers seized power ten years ago. Radio <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, monitored in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION>, said President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials cast their ballots in the elections for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>. In its first reports, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kabul </ORGANIZATION> said voters participated with `` enthusiasm and happiness'' and Tuesday's balloting ended in an orderly manner. But in later broadcasts monitored by the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>, the government station in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the Afghan capital, said rebels fired at some polling stations in four provinces and other areas. The night broadcast said `` in some provinces the elections are taking place in difficult conditions.'' It did not say if there were any casualties. It reported that 147,300 people out of the 955,000 registered voters cast their ballots Tuesday. The broadcast also said there were as many as eight candidates for some legislative seats, and 70 per cent of the candidates were independents. One fourth of the 62 seats in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and 229 in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> are set aside for representatives of anti-communist rebel groups, even if they do not participate. In a message to the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said the elections were `` universal, secret, direct and democratic.'' `` The Republic of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> invites a delegation of the <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> to visit the Republic of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in order to see the process of elections,'' his message said. In a separate message to the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said Afghans and Afghan political forces inside and outside the country were welcome to participate in the elections. About 5 million Afghans have fled the war and live in refugee camps in neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, where rebel groups also have headquarters. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said if the return of the refugees is delayed, `` We are also ready to keep a necessary number of seats in both houses of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> until their final return.'' The elections are being held while U.N.-sponsored peace talks are under way in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. The key issue in those negotiations is the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 Soviet military personnel from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Marxist military officers seized power in an April 1978 coup and Soviet forces intervened in December 1979 to help the government battle the anti-communist guerrillas. In <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, negotiators representing <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> completed five weeks of talks on an Afghan peace settlement. `` There is a constructive atmosphere. I am hopeful that we can in fact succeed shortly,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> diplomat who consults regularly with <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON>. A diplomatic source who spoke on condition of anonymity said <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s ambassador to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shahid </PERSON> <PERSON> Amin </PERSON>, held talks with Soviet Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Yuli </PERSON> <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vorontsov </PERSON>'s portfolio includes the Afghan conflict. The Soviets have announced they plan to withdraw their troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants the Soviets to either cut off aid to the Afghan government or allow <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to continue supporting the insurgents.
