<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> cautiously criticized <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s involvement in the Panamanian standoff and expressed irritation with Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> on Monday as he struggled to pull out a victory in the critical <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary. In a long, final day of campaigning around the state, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> repeatedly likened himself to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who scored an important primary victory in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> in his 1960 presidential campaign. Campaigning before students in <LOCATION> Stevens </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, in his last appearance of the night, he urged that those who support him try to round up a little last-minute help. `` When you go home tonight, make a few phone calls, get a hold of your neighbors. Believe me, your work will make the ... difference,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. Arriving back in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> Monday night, he was asked about his prospects in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>. `` We've worked hard. It looks good. But you never know until the votes come in,'' he said. Earlier, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> recalled <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s success in reversing a round of steel industry price hikes in 1962, and said he would summon <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> to the White House `` fast'' and demand that he drop plans to close a plant in <LOCATION> Kenosha </LOCATION> Polls indicate <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> are locked in a tight race in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, just as they are running neck and neck nationally in the chase for national convention delegates. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor said it was a `` ba