age to make the opposition's case against the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> administration. In time, he sensed, the criticism would wane and he would be better off for the national notoriety he was now receiving.'' Dirksen and <PERSON> Halleck </PERSON> used the Ev and <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> routine to showcase criticism of the Kennedy domestic program. `` It may be called the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Frontier </ORGANIZATION>, but the Kennedy program is the old New Deal taken out of an old warming oven,'' <PERSON> Dirksen </PERSON> said. He scored the administration for `` deficit spending, increased government controls, increases in the government payroll, more welfare statism and that inevitable price which we must pay the piper, more taxes.'' By mid 1962 the Ev and <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> show was fully launched and obviously effective in stating the Republican case. The ridicule evaporated. No Republican leader since has had anything quite resembling his disheveled flair, rumpled charm and widespread appeal.
