 Some 23,000 children and their parents turned the White House south lawn into a kiddie carnival, celebrating an Easter Egg Roll that has been a tradition for 110 years. The children were entertained by an Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> on stilts, by tiny actor <PERSON> Emmanuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> of the `` Webster'' TV show, and by all sorts of cartoon characters from the comic strip `` Peanuts.'' Monday's crowd filled the White House's south grounds where normally helicopters deliver VIPs, bands march and presidents speak. Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> brought his wife, three children and five of his 10 grandchildren. He seemed to have a good time autographing wooden Easter eggs. The rolling was only a small part of the festivities. It consisted of eight youngsters lining up and using wooden spoons to urge their respective eggs toward the finish line. The winners each got a brightly colored wooden egg. So did the losers. On the grounds also were hidden eggs autographed by hundreds of movie stars ranging from Ann-Margret to <PERSON> Efrem </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimbalist </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>.
