<HEAD>Pollsters Say Wisconsin Crucial in Jackson's Effort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s showing in today's <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary will be a key measure of his emergence as a candidate who could have sufficient support to win the Democratic nomination and the presidency, pollsters say. As <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has improved his ability to win votes, the poll analysts noted Monday, the expectations for his campaign have increased. If he has done well, they said, he now needs to do better still. `` It may be a constantly moving target,'' said <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> pollster <PERSON> Keating </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON>. `` The frontier is moving. Twenty percent of the white Democratic vote and all the black vote is not going to win the election in November.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> gained co-frontrunner status when he upset Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> caucuses March 26. No polls were done there to indicate the demographics of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s support. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> then beat <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>'s primary, where <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> got about 20 percent of the white vote. In <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> poll last week put <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s white backing at 30 percent. `` In this state certainly he's a viable candidate,'' said <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Browne </PERSON>, the Journal editor who ran the poll. Though it gave <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> a slim lead, he said, it probably understated <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s support by underestimating black turnout. Blacks have been the most reliable of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s supporters throughout the primary season, voting for him with near-unanimity. At the same time, `` You have to have white voters to be a viable candidate,'' said <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Klett </PERSON>, poll analyst for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` There are some white voters going his way. But it will have to be much larger before he could get the nomination.'' <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary April 19 are crucial to indicate that vote-getting ability, <PERSON> Klett </PERSON> said. `` What happens in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> is going to be pivotal in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' she said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, she suggested, `` has to win one of those states or both.'' `` I would n't put a number on it; it's the number of Democrats that are voting for him,'' <PERSON> Klett </PERSON> said. `` When he gets most of them voting for him, that's when he becomes viable.'' There are other measures as well. In <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, the Journal poll last week showed Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> leading <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in a hypothetical general election race by 50 percent to 36 percent. `` That strikes me as extremely close for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in this state, considering how well known <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is and how well liked -LRB- President -RRB- <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is,'' <PERSON> Browne </PERSON> said. He noted that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> both fared even better in matchups against <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. Another issue in gauging <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s strength is in the nature of the white votes he is attracting. Exit polls in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> said he did best with liberals and lost the blue-collar vote _ critical in the general election _ by 2-1. An analysis of the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> caucus results also indicated that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was not particularly strong in blue-collar precincts, <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said. Still another measure is the share of voters who have a favorable opinion of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Although his rating has improved, the last national survey by <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, done March 19-22, said more white Democrats had an unfavorable opinion of him _ 39 percent _ than the 31 percent favorable. <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> said. Among all white voters it was 46 percent unfavorable to 22 percent favorable, he said. `` You say to yourself, very few white Republicans are going to vote for him. You then write off half the <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> as well, and you're not looking at much of an electoral base,'' said <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>. `` You can see why people will be putting increasing hurdles in front of him.'' `` He is increasing his white vote,'' the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> analyst said. `` If that's the case it may be acceptable to say, Let's see how far you can go with this. Can you reach the point where you can win in November? Twenty percent is not there. I would guess it's not 30 percent.'' I.A. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, chief of polling for the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, said he retained his view that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is able but unlikely to win the nomination and unable to win in November. He cited <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s liberal positions as well as `` an element of racism that exists in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> today. Nonetheless, ` There's already been a profound change. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been to a certain extent legitimized by his very impressive victories,'' said <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. In turn, he said, whatever the outcome, `` <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is legitimizing blacks as legitimate presidential contenders.''
