<HEAD>Jackson Brings In $2 Million Plus in March</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s once-impoverished presidential campaign is showing new fund-raising strength, collecting an impressive $ 2.2 million in donations during March _ more than he raised during all of last year. The sum, coming mostly in contributions of $ 50 or less, represents a dramatic upswing for what <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> frequently boasts is the `` poor campaign with the rich message.'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, finance chairman for the Democratic field's consistent fund-raising leader, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, was laudatory when told Monday about <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s money `` That's a tremendous achievement for Rev. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>,'' he said. `` Anybody that can raise $ 2 million in a month is a hero to me.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor, collected donations totaling more than $ 2.5 million during March, <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> said. Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> raised about $ 1.5 million during March, his campaign said last week. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been picking up most of his money in small contributions through an aggressive direct-mail and telemarketing program. The program banked $ 1 million during March, said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s mail consultant, <PERSON> Mal </PERSON> <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif </LOCATION> He said the returns are the most impressive of any campaign he has ever conducted in 10 years of fund-raising. Farmer said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has gotten contributions averaging $ 135 each over the past 90 days. During all of 1987, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> raised just under $ 2 million, while <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> raised $ 10.8 million. `` He has emerged as a significant player and that's reflected in his financial performance,'' <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` You're beginning to see this as a two-man race and the fund raising is the first benchmark of success. He said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> `` should be very proud'' of his mail returns. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign spokeswoman <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s March receipts surprised even campaign manager <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, who had projected contributions of about $ 1 million. In all, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> collected $ 3 million, including about $ 800,000 in federal matching funds. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> took in about $ 3.4 million, including $ 875,000 in federal matching funds. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s fund-raising boost is timely as the expensive <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary approaches on April 19. `` They're really banking for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said, noting that television ad time in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> is particularly expensive. By contrast, she said, the campaign spent a total of $ 100,000 on today's <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary, with about half going to TV ads. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> generally relies on a grassroots network of volunteers, eliminating the large payroll common to more wealthy campaigns. <PERSON> Warwick </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s mail returns `` have picked up since Super Tuesday,'' when <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> polled first in popular vote and second in delegates across 20 state primaries and caucuses on March 8. In addition to the direct mail campaign, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> raised about $ 140,000 during a two-day fund-raising swing through <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, where national campaign chairman <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> put on a series of fund-raising events. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also collected about $ 120,000 at events in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> prior to the March 26 caucuses where he won a landslide victory. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> got about half his March donations from three days of big-ticket fund-raising events in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON> said.
