<HEAD>With PM-Jackson and PM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here is the text of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s letter to Panamanian strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, dated March 23, 1988. It was released by the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Dear General Noriega:</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 On behalf of all those around the world who see and feel the agony of the Panamanian people, I am writing to appeal to you _ for all of us _ to pursue peace and to put an end to this crisis. The whole forest is being set afire to smoke you out, and the strategy is causing great suffering in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> _ a suffering seen around the world. The livelihood, health and safety of Panamanians are threatened. It is time to put these considerations in the proper perspective for the country's good. A judgment for a greater good must be made. A judgment for <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and for the region must be made! By us working together for peace, we can help heal the sick, feed the hungry and put your country back together. I have been to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> several times and have a great feeling, sensitivity and respect for the people of <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. I agonize daily as I watch the suffering. I have talked with people in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> who now have desperation added to their destitution. I make this appeal reluctantly because I know the history of our country with your country has been a complex one. But suffice it to say that the <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> brought us closer together in harmony. I am appealing for us to relieve the people of the suffering and the bloodshed that may occur. I am anxious to do whatever I can to help alleviate the suffering, but we must act decisively and quickly. I appeal to you for us to find a way to end the crisis now. I am therefore asking <PERSON> Cirilo </PERSON> <PERSON> McSween </PERSON>, my dear friend who has accompanied me to your country on my visits, to see you immediately so that these dialogues surrounding this moral appeal may begin. Repectfully and in Peace, Reverend <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>
