<FIRST>r w PM-InternationalPay     04-05 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-International Pay,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Cheapest, Norway Most Expensive In US Dollars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> had the lowest labor costs last year and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> had the highest as measured in dollars, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says. Average hourly costs in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> went down to $ 1.37 from $ 1.49 in 1986, the department said in its report, released Monday. Though wages more than doubled in Mexican pesos, the exchange value of the peso dropped so far that the dollar cost declined. Brazilian workers saw their wages and benefits rise when measured in cruzados, but in dollar terms there was a decline to $ 1.49 from $ 1.60 an hour because of the low value of the domestic currency. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> are the Third World's two biggest debtors, a situation that tends to drive down the price of their currencies. They were the only countries where the dollar cost of labor was reported to have dropped in the year. The figures take account of the fall in the price of the dollar, and of changes in local pay rates. The costs of social insurance and other benefits are also figured. But the figures do not consider whether some workers are more efficient than others. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s average compensation of $ 17.58 an hour was nearly 13 times <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s dollar amount. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> average of $ 13.46 dollars was almost 10 times <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s. Low wage costs in other countries have long been used by politicians as the reason for protecting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry from imports. Labor unions also have complained against `` exporting jobs,'' arguing that low labor costs in other countries encourage <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employers to set up production there rather than at home. Labor in the newly-industrialized countries of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> remained less than a fifth as costly as in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Of 22 countries surveyed, seven had costs higher than the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rate here. They were, in addition to <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>: <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, $ 17.06; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, $ 16.83; <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, $ 15.14; <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, $ 15.11 dollars; <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, $ 15.08 and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> $ l4 .49 dolllars All 23 countries for which the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had statistics showed an increase of compensation in their own currency, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s relative cost level in 1987 -LRB- of 84 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> costs -RRB- greatly exceeded the previous peak of 72 percent reached in 1986,'' said the report from the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. It noted that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s level was now close to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s. The increase was due largely to the rise of the yen against the dollar. The high value of the domestic currency against the dollar was also the reason for most of the rise in European costs, though they were also raised in <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> by cuts in working hours, the report said.
</TEXT>
