<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Bush Defeat Could Hand Dole New Platform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> stumbles on his way to the White House this November, erstwhile rival <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> could wind up as the nation's top <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> minority leader under a Democratic administration could find himself playing the lead in a 1980s version of the 1960s Ev and <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> <PERSON> Show </PERSON>. It might well be called the <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> show, with <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> being joined by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> to counter a <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> president's programs and present alternatives to them. The Ev of Ev and <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> was <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority leader <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinley </PERSON> <PERSON> Dirksen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. Dirksen teamed with <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Halleck </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> in a regular series of televised news conferences, <PERSON> Dirksen </PERSON> became the undisputed `` Mr. Republican'' of his era. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, crowded out of the 1988 Republican field by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, has returned to his leadership position in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, serving notice he intends to prod the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> into opening its arms to a wider constituency. Republicans should, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> says, address issues of concern to the homeless and the poor and embrace programs to deal with narcotics, day care, education, long-term health care, Medicaid and <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION>. `` We must, above all, give more Americans a reason to come our way and at the same time strengthen the commitment of our staunchest supporters,'' <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> said last week. With a sense of humor that can be dark and biting, <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> will have his own distinct style and image if he emerges as national spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dirksen </PERSON> was `` full of fun and thunder,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Dirksen </ORGANIZATION> biographer <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON>. <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON>, in his 1970 `` Dirksen: Portrait of a Public Man,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> minority leader became a television superstar despite a complete lack of the veneer said to be essential to a politician in the age of television. `` His tousled hair, long his trademark, was an easily recognizable ensign,'' <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON> wrote. `` His deep-throated husky voice, his flamboyant manners and his often astonishing use of a rococo vocabulary all tickled the viewing millions.'' <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> cartoonist <PERSON> Herblock </PERSON> caricatured <PERSON> Dirksen </PERSON> as a melancholy clown, <PERSON> Halleck </PERSON> as a buffoon and straight man. <PERSON> Halleck </PERSON> resented the Ev and Charlie tag. He took his partisanship seriously. But <PERSON> Dirksen </PERSON> said he liked the name, said it reminded him of such other all-American duos as corned beef and cabbage and ham and eggs. Some Republicans said they thought the two stood in poor contrast to <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, the nation's new, youthful and handsome Democratic president. One complained about <PERSON> Dirksen </PERSON>'s `` fuzzy hair'' and <PERSON> Halleck </PERSON>'s `` big red nose. `` None of this troubled Dirksen,'' <PERSON> McNeil </PERSON> wrote, `` for even as the criticisms were being made, he and <PERSON> Halleck </PERSON> were getting television and press coverage to make the opposition's case against the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> administration. In time, he sensed, the criticism would wane and he would be better off for the national notoriety he was now receiving.'' Dirksen and <PERSON> Halleck </PERSON> used the Ev and <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> routine to showcase criticism of the Kennedy domestic program. `` It may be called the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Frontier </ORGANIZATION>, but the Kennedy program is the old New Deal taken out of an old warming oven,'' <PERSON> Dirksen </PERSON> said. He scored the administration for `` deficit spending, increased government controls, increases in the government payroll, more welfare statism and that inevitable price which we must pay the piper, more taxes.'' By mid 1962 the Ev and <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON> show was fully launched and obviously effective in stating the Republican case. The ridicule evaporated. No Republican leader since has had anything quite resembling his disheveled flair, rumpled charm and widespread appeal.
