<FIRST>r a PM-Mecham-Perspective     04-05 0478</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mecham-Perspective,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Impeachment Conviction Places Mecham In Infamous Company</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With his ouster, <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> joined a short but ignominious list of convicted governors, among them a chief executive whoused the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to surround his Capitol and one who declared martial law. Monday's vote by the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to sustain the two articles of impeachment made <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> governor to be impeached and removed from office in 59 years. Legal scholars say impeachment was devised in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> used it as a way to flex its muscle against kings and ministers. Impeachment was brought to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in colonial days as a way to protect democracy. `` It's basically, ` You're fired.' Impeachment is a way to get out of office those officials that violate the public trust,'' said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> law professor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Glennon </PERSON>. Had he been acquitted, <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON> would have joined the likes of <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, the flamboyant `` Kingfish'' of <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, among governors who were impeached by legislators but not convicted. Instead, he became one of seven chief executives who have been removed from office, including the first governor of <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and a pair of governors in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>. Gov. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> was removed in 1871 for misappropriating school funds, but the impeachment proceedings subsequently were expunged from the legislative record and in 1888 he was elected to another term as governor. Gov. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> was removed in 1923 after he declared martial law and ordered the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to disband a grand jury that was investigating him. Gov. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, also of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, used equally strong tactics to try to prevent an investigation of him. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> ordered the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to surround the Capitol to prevent the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> from assembling to conduct the probe. <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, who was removed in 1929, was the last governor ousted from office by legislators before <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>. Also on the list is Gov. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holden </PERSON> of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, who was removed in 1871 after he unconstitutionally suspended the right of habeas corpus and sent militia to quell violence by the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION>, which was accused of murders aimed at frightening blacks into not voting. In <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, the governor need only commit `` high crimes, misdemeanors, or malfeasance'' to face impeachment. <PERSON> Mecham </PERSON>, convicted of obstruction of justice and misusing funds, is the first <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> governor to be impeached. <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> was impeached by <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>' colonial Assembly in 1781. Among the charges was that he had fled with unseemly haste when British troops attacked the capital. Although the Assembly soon backed down, <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> insisted on a trial and won vindication. Long was impeached on charges of misusing state funds in 1929. The case was dropped when 15 senators _ enough to block conviction _ announced their support for the governor.
