<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two jet warplane crashes near <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> nuclear power plants have increased criticism of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> pilot-training practices, and one newspaper's coverage of the issue has angered the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. Tens of thousands of West German protesters joined traditional Easter peace marches and vigils that began Saturday and lasted through Monday. This year the demonstrators not only called for scrapping nuclear arms, but they also protested the two air crashes that occurred near atomic power plants just over 24 hours of each other last week. The Association for <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION>, a West German organization of private pilots, joined the protesters in demanding that <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> keep its warplanes away from nuclear power plants. `` The chance of the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident was more than likely very slim, but it happened anyway,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, spokesman for the group, pointed out in a radio interview. The respected <ORGANIZATION> Wickert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> polled West Germans and found that 15 percent want <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> to halt its low-level military training flights over this nation. Two-thirds of the 1,710 people polled said such flights were necessary but the number should be reduced, the Tuebingen-based institute said Saturday. A French Mirage jet fighter crashed on March 30 one mile from a nuclear power plant in the southern state of <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION>, killing the pilot. `` We escaped the worst imaginable accident by only a split-second,'' <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinzierl </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Bavarian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nature </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION>, said after the crash. One day later, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> F-16 fighter jet crashed in the southern town of <LOCATION> Forst </LOCATION>, demolishing three houses and killing a resident and the pilot. The accident occurred nine miles east of another nuclear power plant. Federal officials say nuclear power plants are sufficiently protected from even a direct hit by falling warplanes, but protesters say such assurances are based only on theory. West German newspapers have given intense coverage to the debate of the possible threat from jet warplane crashes. On Sunday, the mass-circulation <ORGANIZATION> Bild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sonntag </ORGANIZATION> newspaper printed a front-page article headlined `` This Junk Flies Over Our Heads,'' accompanied by what it said was pictures of a patched-up <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> F-16. The newspaper quoted an unidentified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employee at <LOCATION> Sembach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION>, located near the southwest city of <LOCATION> Kaiserslautern </LOCATION>, as saying poor maintenance and a shortage of spare parts made <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> F-16 planes unsafe. The report said 110,000 low-level military practice flights were conducted over <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> annually by seven NATO-member air forces, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military officials were upset over what he described as <ORGANIZATION> Bild </ORGANIZATION>'s `` highly inaccurate report.'' He said he could not verify how many low-level flights were made over <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The spokesman said the Americans would coordinate a response to the <ORGANIZATION> Bild </ORGANIZATION> article because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is but one of several countries involved in low-level training flights here. He declined to elaborate. Other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> nations that regularly train in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> airspace include <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. Another spokesman told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview from <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> European headquarters at <LOCATION> Ramstein </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Air </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Base </LOCATION> that the photograph in <LOCATION> Bild </LOCATION> was not of an F-16. `` The Bild picture shows a non-operational F-4 which has been parked near the -LRB- perimeter -RRB- fence on Sembach for some time,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. `` It's not an F-16 and does n't even have a motor. It's only used by technicians to practice fuselage-patching so they will be proficient in getting a damaged airplane back in the air in wartime,'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> said.
