<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The deaths of a distraught Japanese-born woman and her two young daughters in a house fire was a type of Japanese murder-suicide intended to prevent the children from becoming orphans, police said. Physical evidence found at the home and interviews with the woman's husband led to that conclusion, Detective Sgt. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Haradon </PERSON> said Monday. <PERSON> Mitsue </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakai </PERSON>, 28, was found Sunday in a bedroom along with her daughters, <PERSON> Seira </PERSON> <PERSON> Candy </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakai </PERSON>, 5, and <PERSON> Rina </PERSON> <PERSON> Stephanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakai </PERSON>, 4. All three died of smoke inhalation, <PERSON> Haradon </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mitsue </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hideo </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakai </PERSON> had been having marital problems, the investigator said. The murder-suicide, known in Japanese as oyako shinju, is a tradition in which parents planning suicide feel obliged to kill their children so they will not be orphans. Mrs. <PERSON> Sakai </PERSON>, who moved to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, about eight years ago, and her husband, <PERSON> Hideo </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Yokohama </LOCATION>, were described by acquaintances as quiet and hard-working people. Mrs. <PERSON> Sakai </PERSON> worked at the <LOCATION> Mitsuyoshi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> restaurant in <LOCATION> Anaheim </LOCATION>. Her husband is head chef at the <LOCATION> Amagi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Japanese </LOCATION> restaurant in <LOCATION> Buena </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Yoshikazu </PERSON> <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON>, owner of the <LOCATION> Amagi </LOCATION> restaurant, said the couple met at his establishment about seven years ago when Mrs. <PERSON> Sakai </PERSON> worked there as a waitress. `` If she lost hope or something, she can not let the children live,'' <PERSON> Suzuki </PERSON> said. `` I know of many cases in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> like that.'' An estimated 300 cases of oyako shinju are reported each year in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, authorities said. The tragedy recalled the case of <PERSON> Fumiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimura </PERSON>, a Japanese-born woman whose two young children died when she walked into the sea with them at <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION> in 1985. Her mother-child suicide attempt was carried out in shame over her husband's alleged adultery. Mrs. <PERSON> Kimura </PERSON> pleaded guilty to voluntary manslaughter and was placed on five years' probation. Although oyako shinju is illegal in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, it is considered an honorable way to die and lingers in the culture, said <PERSON> Mamoru </PERSON> <PERSON> Iga </PERSON>, a professor of sociology at <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Northridge </ORGANIZATION>, and author of `` The Thorn in the Chrysanthemum: Suicide and Economic Success in Modern <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Iga </PERSON> said the crime is most often committed by mothers who have money problems or bad marriages.
