<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic presidential contender <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> carved out a narrow lead over rival <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> early Tuesday as votes were counted in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>'s caucuses. Each of the front-runners had hoped for a solid win to provide `` bounce'' going into Tuesday's <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> primary, but there was no clear winner when counting was called off for the night With 1,234 of 2,784 precincts reporting, or 44 percent, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had 46 percent to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 40 percent. <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> lagged far behind, with 4 percent, and Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> was n't registering any support from the Monday night caucuses Late Monday, preliminary returns from a party sampling of 130 precincts gave <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> a 2-1 lead over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. But when <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> precincts began weighing in with tallies early Tuesday morning, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' lead disappeared in a <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> surge. Then <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> battled his way back. The Democratic party quit counting for the night at about 4:30 a.m. EDT. The results were still too incomplete to determine conclusively how many national convention delegates each candidate won. Meanwhile, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> came under fire for his contact with Panamanian strongman <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. Earlier, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> called <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s involvement in the <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> situation a `` bad idea.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> also criticized <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s correspondence with <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, but he blasted <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for being `` absolutely timid'' of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor dismissed <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> and his comments: `` I do n't know what he's serious about.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> were joined by <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> campaigning across <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> on Monday. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> is trailing badly in his effort to win here and keep his campaign alive, while <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> needs a good showing in the state to boost his faltering effort. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> urged voters in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> to send a message Tuesday. `` We're not going to follow the pollsters; we're going to elect the man best qualified to be president,'' he said, quipping: `` <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> agrees with that too.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' aides emphasized how close the race is in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Loftus </PERSON>, speaker of the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> state assembly and a <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> backer, said the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor `` is going to win by enough _ three, four or five points.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, the front-runners in both states, awaited the slow dribble of results from the 2,784 precinct caucuses in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> that will divide 45 national convention delegates. The Republicans were holding caucuses Monday night in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> as well as the Democrats. With Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> already having locked up the nomination, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s effort to win some of the state's 36 <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> delegates was a symbolic gesture. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> are the front-runners in the AP delegate count. Before the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> resul