<HEAD>University Opening Doors To Mark `Stand In Schoolhouse Door'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Several players in a national desegregation drama will return to the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alabama </ORGANIZATION> to mark the 25th anniversary of the day then-Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> tried to block the entrance of two black students. To commemorate the event June 11 _ a milestone in the civil rights struggle _ the university will host a three-day symposium called `` Opening Doors,'' featuring some of the nation's leading scholars on race relations. The university `` felt the best way to recognize this event was through a symposium that focuses not only on the history of race relations, the stand in the door, but also the present and future of race relations,'' said Professor <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Culpepper </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, who is writing a book on that era. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> and <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Knopke </PERSON>, a university official helping to arrange the symposium, said they believe the school was an unwilling pawn in power plays between <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> and the administration of President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. `` The university had a very substantive, productive plan for integrating,'' <PERSON> Knopke </PERSON> said. `` In the late 1950s and early 1960s the administration and others were looking seriously at ways to integrate. There was a plan already in place for doing that when <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> started speaking. `` The university was just in the middle of it.'' Among those who have agreed to take part in the symposium, which will end June 11, is <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Katzenbach </PERSON>, who as assistant attorney general faced off with <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> in the doorway of Foster Auditorium, a few hours before students <PERSON> Vivian </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hood </PERSON> walked in to register. Also agreeing to take part are <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON>, now Mrs. <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, president of the university at the time; then-Dean <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackburn </PERSON>, and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> LeMaistre </PERSON>, a prominent <LOCATION> Tuscaloosa </LOCATION> businessman who organized community support for the school's desegregation. `` We wanted to bring back some of the individuals who were involved in the <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> stand to share their perspectives,'' <PERSON> Knopke </PERSON> said. `` We want to make something positive out of it, something productive and informative.'' Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., was invited to represent his slain brothers, the president and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, who was attorney general in 1963, but he said he had another commitment <PERSON> Knopke </PERSON> said he doubted that <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, who has been in poor health, will be able to attend, but that documentary footage of the governor's stand will be shown. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> has said he made his stand to reduce the possibility of violence at the university, although critics said it increased tensions. An array of scholars will present papers dealing with race relations today and what can be expected in the future, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said. `` There is always in the minds of Alabamians the fact that 25 years later we are far different than in 1963, yet we still sometimes get in our minds that we're frozen in 1963,'' he said. `` What happened then is history and we're a far different people than we were then.'' The school-door standoff, <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said, `` was a test of wills between <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> administration, the state of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and federal authorities.'' <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, he said, has since acknowledged that he made `` a terrible public relations mistake.'' <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> said the university, with 10 percent black enrollment today, `` is so long past all that in the actual workings of this institution and carrying out its mission that sometimes we have to pinch ourselves to see if that were really us and if it were, what does it have to do with us now.'' That, he said, is the purpose of the symposium.
