<HEAD>Government Opens Case Against Man Accused of Collaborating With
Nazis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government is trying to deport a Latvian accused of collaborating with the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in a case described by one federal official as so strong `` I would not want to be defending it.'' <PERSON> Konrads </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalejs </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1959 saying he was a farmer in <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>. What he failed to disclose, the government maintains, is that he belonged to a pro-Nazi police unit in World War II that killed Jews by the thousands. `` Its main task was essentially rounding people up, guarding them and killing them,'' said <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilberg </PERSON>, a political science professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> and an expert on the Holocaust. <PERSON> Hilberg </PERSON> was the government's main witness Monday as the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> opened deportation hearings. The government said it has evidence that <PERSON> Kalejs </PERSON> was a commander in the <ORGANIZATION> Latvian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auxiliary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>, whose leader was convicted in 1979 of the murders of at least 13,000 people from 1941-44. In 1985 the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> filed for <PERSON> Kalejs </PERSON>' deportation, saying he lied on his entrance visa and would not have been admitted to this country if officials had known about his past. The government's case is expected to last several weeks. During that time, attorneys plan to summon witnesses who survived the <LOCATION> Latvian </LOCATION> death camps and present documents detailing the actions of <PERSON> Kalejs </PERSON> and