<HEAD>Compromise To Create Second Judgeship in Robeson County</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers agreed to support a second <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judgeship for racially tense <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, eliminating the need for a special legislative session sought by supporters of a slain Indian judicial candidate. Monday's agreement came during a three-hour meeting in <LOCATION> Lumberton </LOCATION> between Lt. Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> legislators and members of the campaign committee of <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>, who was killed March 26 in what police called a domestic dispute. If approved by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in its June session, Republican Gov. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> could appoint a new <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> judge from <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said he supported the agreement and pledged he would appoint a minority, and probably an Indian. <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON>'s supporters had pressured the governor to call a special legislative session to amend state law to allow another minority candidate to run for the present judgeship. Filing for the judgeship closed in February, and state law does not allow a replacement for a candidate who dies more than 30 days after the filing period ends. The judgeship was one of nine established last year in areas with predominantly black or Indian populations in an effort to increase the number of minority judges. Rep. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Locks </PERSON>, a black <LOCATION> Robeson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> leader who was part of Monday's negotiations, was unenthusiastic about the compromise. `` But we were trying to find some way to diffuse the kinds of problems we currently