<SECOND>PM-Sedition Trial,0582</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Deliberates Complicated Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Jury to resume deliberations at 10:30 a.m. CDT.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The federal trial of three white supremacist leaders and six other men accused of plotting to overthrow the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government through violence has gone to the jury. `` It's all in Yahweh's hands,'' <PERSON> Sheila </PERSON> <PERSON> Beam </PERSON>, wife of supremacist leader <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Beam </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said after the jury began deliberations Monday. `` If the truth is known, they'll be acquitted.'' <PERSON> Yahweh </PERSON> is a Hebrew name for God. The jury was to resume deliberations today. The case involves 13 defendants, nine of whom are charged with seditious conspiracy, or conspiring to overthrow the government. A conviction carries a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison. In addition, five of the defendants are accused of conspiring to kill federal officials and two are charged with interstate transportation of stolen money. The maximum penalty for murder conspiracy is life in prison. The stiffest punishment for transporting stolen money is 10 years. Five of the defendants are in prison for other crimes. In addition to <PERSON> Beam </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, the supremacist leaders are <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON>, 63, of <LOCATION> Cohoctah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, 70 of <LOCATION> Hayden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. Miles, pastor of the <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>, is the author of a newsletter that attacked Jews and the federal government. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> is the founder of the white supremacist group <ORGANIZATION> Aryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Beam </PERSON> is a former <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> recruiter who left the <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 and became a representative for the Aryan Nations. The government alleged that the defendants agreed to try to bring down the government by force during an Aryan Nations congress in 1983. The government contended that some of the defendants went on to commit a series of robberies to finance their activities. The robberies netted about $ 4.1 million, of which about $ 1 million is unaccounted for, the government said. In closing arguments Monday, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzhugh </PERSON> said <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>, <PERSON> Beam </PERSON> and <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> came up with the idea for overthrowing the government. <PERSON> Fitzhugh </PERSON> said the sedition defendants maintained they hoped to bring about a white supremacist nation through a peaceful move to the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>. But, he said, if that was the case, why did: _ Defendant <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> say in a taped conversation that he needed to bomb some major telephone facility _ Defendant <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierce </PERSON> become a member of The Order, a violent group that committed armed robberies, by taking an oath declaring a `` full state of war'' _ The Covenant, The Sword and The Arm of The Lord _ an Arkansas-based supremacist group _ collect an arsenal of automatic weapons, silencers, grenades and other explosives and embark on robberies, bombings and murders During the trial, the defense attacked the credibility of government witnesses. But <PERSON> Fitzhugh </PERSON> told jurors, `` Plots made in hell do n't have angels as partners.'' Attorney <PERSON> N.C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Deday </PERSON> <PERSON> LaRene </PERSON>, representing Miles, said in his closing argument Monday that the government's key witness, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON>, `` had serious delusions.'' <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON> belonged to the <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> group. <PERSON> LaRene </PERSON> said <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON> made up the story about a conspiracy hatched at <LOCATION> Hayden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> because he lost an appeal of his racketeering conviction and was looking for a way out of prison. The defense attorney said that in three earlier reports about supremacist activities, <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON> never mentioned that alleged meeting.
