<HEAD>Wedtech Witness: Contractor Tried to Sell to Iran, Iraq and Saudi
Arabia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> ex-Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> executive claims the defense contractor sought help from a <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabian </LOCATION> prince and friends of Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> 3rd in an attempt to sell military equipment to <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> countries. But negotiations to sell bridge pontoons and other supplies to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> eventually fell through, former <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> Vice Chairman <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> testified Monday. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, one of four former <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> officials testifying at the racketeering trial of Rep. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> and six others in exchange for leniency, was asked about the scandal-plagued company's <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> dealings in his 14th day on the witness stand. The jury was not present during the questioning and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> Motley </PERSON> later ruled the topic inadmissible because, she said, it did n't provide any evidence that a crime had been committed but would unduly prejudice the jury. <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> and the six others are charged with turning the now-bankrupt <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> into a racketeering enterprise that paid out millions of dollars in bribes. Once a small machine shop in the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> grew into a multimillion-dollar manufacturer through a program that set aside federal contracts without competitive bidding for minority-owned companies. Prosecutors allege <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON> and others helped <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> falsely portray itself as a minority concern eligible for the no-bid program. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> denied that <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> had acted on behalf of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. `` No, we were acting as <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, one of four ex-Wedtech executives to plead guilty to state and federal corruption charges. `` We believed we could do it legally.'' `` You knew you could never legally have gotten an export license -LRB- to sell military equipment -RRB-?'' asked defense attorney <PERSON> Dominic </PERSON> <PERSON> Amorosa </PERSON>. `` It crossed my mind,'' said <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, who did not elaborate. Asked if <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s close friend and former business associate, had said he could help obtain export licenses, <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> replied, `` It never got to that point.'' <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> previously testified that <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> paid <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> $ 800,000 for his `` influence with <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> has not been accused of wrongdoing in the case. The witness said company officials spoke with <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> `` on two or three occasions'' about foreign deals. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON> also said a former <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> financial adviser, <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Franklyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON>, was `` a conduit in trying to sell arms to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Cristina </PERSON> <PERSON> Arguedas </PERSON>, when called for comment, said, `` I've never heard this allegation before, and I continue to deny that <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> has engaged in any illegal conduct.'' Both <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chinn </PERSON> are under federal indictment, accused of extracting payoffs from <ORGANIZATION> Wedtech </ORGANIZATION> for allegedly influencing <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> and other officials.
