<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ortega Calls U.S. Aid Illegal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> called an aid package the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approved last week for the Contra rebels illegal. His comments came Monday, one day before the third round of talks between military leaders for the leftist government and the Contra rebels aimed at working out the technical details of the 60-day cease-fire that began Friday. In another development, reports reaching <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> indicated that some fighting between <LOCATION> Sandinistas </LOCATION> and Contras has occurred despite the truce. `` We can not accept any type of aid to the Contras because it would be legitimizing the interventionist policy of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> told reporters. `` It is illegal because the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has no right to decide what type of government <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> ought to have.'' Under a 60-day cease-fire agreement signed March 23 in the southern border town of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, the Contras agreed to accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral organization, such as the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> said they would grant freedom of expression and amnesty to political prisoners and will allow rebel leaders to take part in national talks. In today's technical talks, also to be held in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> representatives will hammer out technical details of the truce. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Friday signed the aid package for the rebels and victims of the fighting that has battered <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> for more than six years. Only $ 17.7 million of the $ 48 million package was directed to the rebels, and the aid package contains no provision for weapons. Despite the cease-fire, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION>, an underground rebel station, quoted <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> on Monday as saying that Sandinista troops had been firing on rebels. A transcript of the broadcast also quoted Contra leader <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON> as saying the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> continued bombing civilian towns in the rural north. The pro-government newspaper, <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nuevo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diario </ORGANIZATION>, reported that Contra forces attacked a Sandinista army patrol Saturday, killing two soldiers and injuring three near the town of <LOCATION> Condega </LOCATION>, about 120 miles north of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said there were no reports of cease-fire violations. The cease-fire was arranged to give both sides time to work out a permanent truce in the war, which has killed more than 40,000 people. Under the peace plan, the rebels are to gather in cease-fire zones during the first two weeks of April. Two days of meetings last week ended with both sides agreeing only to set up five cease-fire zones. They failed to work out the size of the areas or security for the Contras. The peace agreement does not mention disarming the rebels, and the Contras claim they will never surrender their weapons. The <PERSON> Sandinistas </PERSON> met the first step of the agreement by releasing 100 political prisoners March 27. The remaining 3,300 political prisoners are to be released gradually as the terms of the pact are met. The Contras charge the Sandinistas only released 10 political prisoners that they requested. They say the others served only a few weeks or were common criminals. The Sandinistas came to power in a revolution that ousted the late President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> in July 1979. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> supported the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> initially, but in 1981 began financing the Contras.
