<HEAD>Defense Files Motion To Supress Evidence In Friedland Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY HELEN GILLESPIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers for a former state senator claimed he was suffering from the effects of being drugged and tortured when he made statements to authorities on his return to this country from foreign custody. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON>, who disappeared just before he was to go to prison on a kickback conviction and spent two years on the lam, was treated so badly by authorities in the <LOCATION> Maldive </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> that he began hallucinating the night before he was turned over to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, the attorneys say. `` Mr. <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> hallucinated that the prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> told him to convert and he would be released,'' said a motion filed by the lawyers last week. The motion, filed Thursday before Chief U.S. District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON>, seeks to suppress statements <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> made to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agents en route from the <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> islands to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in December 1987. <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> does not remember being read his rights or waiving his rights to an attorney during the flight, the motion said. It also said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agents manipulated <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> to obtain the statements. Defense attorneys also filed motions last week to dismiss 35 of the 90 counts in a federal indictment charging <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> with masterminding a $ 20 million swindle of a pension fund. <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON>, 50, is scheduled to go on trial Sept. 7 on charges he set up a bogus mortgage company in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to bilk the pension fund of Teamsters Local 701 in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION>. Court documents do not indicate the nature of the statements <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> allegedly made to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Deputy Marshal <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> <PERSON> Deem </PERSON> and Special Agent <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sommero </PERSON> during the flight. First Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Chertoff </PERSON> declined comment on the statements Monday but said they may be made public during a May 13 pretrial hearing before <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON>. <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> faked his death in a bogus scuba-diving accident in September 1985, weeks before he was to be sentenced for a 1980 kickback conviction involving the same pension fund. An indictment alleges <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON>, a disbarred attorney, engineered the second scam while working as a government informant. In 26 months on the lam, <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> traveled through <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> before settling in the <LOCATION> Maldives </LOCATION>, where he ran a scuba-diving business for 18 months using an alias. By the time he was placed in the custody of that country's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on Dec. 12, <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> had been named the most wanted fugitive by the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> Marshal's office. While in foreign custody, <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> was kept in a room with a board for a mattress and an overflowing toilet, fed spoiled food, injected with drugs and beaten when he tried to sleep, his attorneys say. Officials there also gave him daily injections of <LOCATION> Talacen </LOCATION>, a mild narcotic, and Valium, an anti-anxiety drug, laced his tea with hallucinogenics, and gave him other drugs, the motion said. After 12 days in custody, `` due to complete lack of sleep, substantial drug consumption, exhaustion and pain, Mr. <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> was mentally and physically exhausted,'' the motion said. While in this condition, <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> was handed over to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agents who escorted him back to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Defense attorneys <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Yacovelle </PERSON> did not return calls Monday. Attempts to contact Maldiven officials were unsuccessful. Calls to the <LOCATION> Maldiven </LOCATION> consulate in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> were not returned. <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON> faces a maximum sentence of seven years in prison for his disappearance and up to 150 years in prison if convicted of charges stemming from the second pension fund case.
