curity,'' <PERSON> Hedrick </PERSON> said. `` Something was overlooked.'' <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON>, formerly of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, was serving a life sentence without chance of parole for the 1981 slaying of <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> police officer <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>, who was shot several times in the head with his own service revolver. <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> had been investigating another officer's report of a suspicious person. At the time of the killing, <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON> was free on bond after being charged with shooting a <LOCATION> Huber </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Heights </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, police officer with a sawed-off shotgun. <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON> was a successful businessman who used the money from his crimes for business ventures. When he was arrested, he owned a bar, at least two houses and several automobiles. <LOCATION> Huntington </LOCATION> police officers, who usually patrol traffic alone, teamed up in pairs Monday. `` It's always better to have two people. A suspect is less likely to shoot that way,'' said Lt. <PERSON> Toby </PERSON> <PERSON> Shy </PERSON>.
