<TEXT>
 A judge has set aside a $ 300,000 jury award to an 11-year-old girl who sued her father for hitting her in the face, saying the amount was excessive. `` I was shocked at the verdict,'' Circuit Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plummer </PERSON> said Monday. `` That's the simplest way I can put it.'' He ordered a new trial to decide what compensation <PERSON> Samantha </PERSON> <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON> should receive from her father, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON>, a prominent lawyer. But he cautioned that the girl's emotional health must be considered before another trial can begin. The lawsuit stemmed from an incident Jan. 19, 1985, during which <PERSON> Samantha </PERSON> was hit in the face after she interrupted an argument between her parents. According to testimony at the three-day trial in January, <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON>, were arguing at the family's <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Church </LOCATION> home when <PERSON> Samantha </PERSON>, then 8 years old, repeatedly told her father to stop shouting because she was trying to sleep. <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON>, 45, told the jury that he followed his daughter upstairs to her bedroom and, while he was trying to spank her on the buttocks, she flipped over, cursed him with a word she had been reprimanded for using before, and he slapped her on the face. `` This is a slap-in-the-face case, maybe too hard,'' but nonetheless parental chastisement for repeated use of profanity, said <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sattler </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Baskin </PERSON>'s attorneys. <PERSON> Sattler </PERSON> argued Monday that the award, which included interest dating to the incident, was out of proportion to the injury, which he described as a temporary bruise. <PERSON> Samantha </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Duff </PERSON>, agreed there was limited ph