<TEXT>
 A fired teaching assistant's abilities were n't marred by the native African head wrap she wore in class, and she ca n't be denied unemployment benefits for that reason, a judge has ruled. The <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> improperly witheld compensation from <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGlothin </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Hinds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> ruled recently. The 34-year-old <PERSON> McGlothin </PERSON> was dismissed as a teaching assistant at <ORGANIZATION> Whitfield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> on March 17, 1987. Principal <PERSON> Kisiah </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolan </PERSON> recommended the firing because <PERSON> McGlothin </PERSON> refused to stop wearing head wraps, court records show. <PERSON> McGlothin </PERSON> went to court because she was refused unemployment compensation. A commission referee said her firing was based on misconduct, and that disqualified her from benefits. `` There was absolutely no showing that <PERSON> McGlothin </PERSON>'s dress in any way affected her performance or caused a disruption,'' <PERSON> Banks </PERSON> said in the ruling last week. `` Such practices are protected by the First Amendment to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> Constitution and can not be ` misconduct' within the meaning of the -LRB- unemployment compensation -RRB- statute, so as to deny unemployment benefits.'' `` I hope the case will set a precedent for serious-minded people of our culture and religion,'' <PERSON> McGlothin </PERSON> said. `` I'd like to commend Judge Banks.'' <PERSON> McGlothin </PERSON>, who hopes to become a certified teacher, testi