sted soldier. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>STUTTGART, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> helicopter crashed in southern <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> today, killing the American pilot and a West German <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> employee, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> said. There were no other casualties in the 9 a.m. crash near <LOCATION> Nabern </LOCATION>, 25 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Stuttgart </LOCATION>, according to a statement by the Stuttgart-based <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 7th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION>. The statement identified the dead pilot as 1st Lt. <PERSON> Glen </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, 28, who was assigned to <ORGANIZATION> Headquarters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, 4th Battalion, 159th Aviation, 11th Aviation Brigade, in <LOCATION> Schwaebisch </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hall </LOCATION>, near <LOCATION> Stuttgart </LOCATION>. The Army could not provide his hometown. <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> is survived by his wife. The second victim was a West German employee of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, who was a passenger on the aircraft, the statement said. His name was being withheld until his next of kin had been notified, the <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> said. A board of officers from the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Fort </PERSON> <PERSON> Rucker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ala. </LOCATION>, was scheduled to arrive in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> Wednesday to investigate the cause of the crash of the OH-58A Kiowa helicopter, the statement added. `` The helicopter was on a routine support mission. There were no weapons or ammunition on board,'' <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Hilda </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodhand </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. <LOCATION> Stuttgart </LOCATION> police said the helicopter went down in an open area, apparently after running into tree branches in a heavy fog. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military officials immediately cordoned off the site. It was the third crash of a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> military aircraft in less than a week. A French Mirage jet fighter crashed on March 30 one mile from a nuclear power plant in the southern state of <LOCATION> Bavaria </LOCATION>, killing the pilot. One day later, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> F-16 fighter jet crashed into the southern town of <LOCATION> Forst </LOCATION>, demolishing three houses and killing a resident and the pilot.
