<SECOND>AM-Romania,0618</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Villages to Vanish to Get More Land For State Farms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Romanian officials have spelled out plans to erase 7,000 villages and form big agricultural-industrial centers by the year 2000, a move that critics of the regime say will ruin traditional country life. The huge project unveiled last month by <ORGANIZATION> Romanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Nicolae </PERSON> <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> calls for radical cuts in the number of villages, from 13,000 to only 5,000 or 6,000. A statement published March 4 in the party daily <PERSON> Scinteia </PERSON> said the move aims `` to eradicate basic differences betweeen villages and cities and ensure the harmonious development of all areas of the country.'' Romanian officials writing in the government press say the program is intended to gain about 765,600 acres of land for use by state-owned collective farms. They say this will be achieved by banning construction of one-family homes and concentrating several families in city-style apartment blocks. Thousands of such apartment blocks _ many with only rudimentary amenities _ have been built since 1986, when a new systematization law on getting more farmland was passed. Families put into such apartment blocks lose their traditional small plots, which are regarded as a staple provider of food in the shortage-plagued Communist nation, and they must use communal facilities to grow food and raise livestock. About 8,300 apartments were built in 15 rural communities around <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> last year, according to official figures. `` The entire project amounts to the destruction of villages, the traditional family cell of Romanians,'' said <PERSON> Mihnea </PERSON> <PERSON> Berindei </PERSON>, a Romanian emigre living in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, in a telephone interview with the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday. <PERSON> Berindei </PERSON>, who is spokesman of the Paris-based League for the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, said thousands of churches also were threatened with demolition under the `` systematization plans,'' the official title for the project to reduce the number of villages. `` This project has no equivalent in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' he said. In 1981, <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> launched a `` new agricultural revolution'' aimed at boosting disappointing cereal outputs, the source of widespread food shortages and rationing. Romanian agriculture has been plagued by lack of incentives, fodder shortages for private livestock and a system of contracting which forces farmers to sell their produce to the state under obligatory contracts against low prices. Despite official promises in December to enable each Romanian to buy about 13 pounds of meat a month on average, meat is still rationed to a little more than two pounds per capita a month and is in short supply, Romanian sources say. Addressing a conference of local government officials in <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> on March 3, <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> announced the villages project will entail the merger of scores of villages and communes into 558 agricultural-industrial centers, viewed as communities linking rural and town life. The nationwide undertaking is likely to lead to the relocation of hundreds of thousands of villagers from old family homes to two-or three-story apartment blocks with communal kitchens and sanitary installations. <PERSON> Ceausescu </PERSON> urged in his speech that doctors, teachers and farm engineers who live in nearby towns and commute daily to the villages where they are employed should move into the rural apartment blocks starting this year. Some apartments destined for the `` village intelligentsia'' have already been built and officials say the program will be completed by 1989. Half of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>'s population of 23 million resides in the country, according to official figures. The collectivized agriculture is almost fully state-owned, except for 9 percent of farmland permitted to peasants as small private plots around their homes or in hilly areas where collectivization was not possible.
</TEXT>
