<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government on Tuesday decided to train scientists to serve as astronauts in a Soviet space flight. <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> will also build a satellite under the plan, which calls for Austrian participation in several Soviet space projects. Soviet Premier <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryzhkov </PERSON> raised the idea in June on a visit to <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>. Possible candidates for Austrian participation in a space flight will be sought through newspaper and trade journal advertisements. The education in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is to last two years, the <ORGANIZATION> Austria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. Austrian scientists have already made proposals for space experiments, and researchers at <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Graz </LOCATION> are working on a small satellite to place outside the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> space station `` Mir.'' The cost of Austrian participation in a Soviet space mission, tentatively set for 1992, was estimated at $ 13 million.
