<HEAD>TV Version of USA Today Taking Shape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In case anyone had any doubts, the staff preparing `` USA Today: The Television Show'' for its fall debut demonstrated Tuesday that the video version of the national newspaper will mirror the publication that spawned it. At a news conference at the newspaper's offices just outside <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the executive producer and four hosts of the program discussed a show they said will offer segments that people find interesting and understandable, graphics that will glitter and stories that will supplement _ not compete with _ the network news. `` If we ca n't do it better or different, we're not going to do it,'' the show's executive producer, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, said. `` Once you've looked at a burning ship in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> four or five times, you do n't want to look at it any more.'' The nighttime show premieres Sept. 12. It will run for 30 minutes every weeknight and have an hour-long weekend edition. Like the newspaper, it will have segments devoted to news, lifestyle, sports and business, focusing on articles that will appear in <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> Today the next morning. <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> said the producers so far had 118 firm contracts with television stations across the country to broadcast the program, covering 85 percent of the country. Those agreements make the show more available to early evening viewers than any program with the exception of `` Wheel of Fortune,'' said <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, who guided <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' show for nearly a decade The team selected to host the program include <PERSON> Edie </PERSON> <PERSON> Magnus </PERSON>, hired from <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>'s `` World News This Morning'' to anchor the `` Front-Page'' segment; and <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, a former contributing correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </O