<HEAD>Dog Helps Young Men Find Counterfeit Millions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two young men who noticed their dog digging in a brush-covered field helped recover an estimated $ 10 million to $ 12 million in counterfeit cash that <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> police had been seeking since 1976. The men, whose names were withheld, dug up two garbage bags stuffed with about $ 4 million in bogus <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal reserve banknotes before calling police. <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canadian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mounted </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> officers, digging Monday, found an additional $ 8 million in uncut sheets of counterfeit $ 100, $ 50 and $ 20 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bills described as `` really good quality.'' Cpl. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Danton </PERSON> of the Vancouver RCMP commercial crime squad said an investigation had produced suspects but no arrests. He said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> agents and the <ORGANIZATION> RCMP </ORGANIZATION> had been looking for the money since 1976 when `` quite a bit'' of the same batch was seized. `` We knew it was buried but we thought it was somewhere else,'' he said. `` We knew it was around.'' `` We estimate it at about $ 10 million to $ 12 million,'' said <PERSON> Danton </PERSON>. `` We have n't had time to count it yet. We're just going by thickness. It filled the trunk of a car pretty good.''
