<HEAD>Half Of Rape Victims Are Adolescents; Report Urges Pediatric
Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ELK GROVE VILLAGE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 While nearly 50 percent of reported rape victims are adolescents, many pediatricians are ill-equipped to treat them, the American <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatrics </ORGANIZATION> says in urging better training to handle sexual assault victims. In a policy statement published in the April issue of its monthly journal, Pediatrics, the academy notes that pediatricians frequently serve in emergency rooms as the primary health-care provider in adolescent rapes. Pediatricians `` need to be sensitive to the acute emotional problems, not to do things that might cause further psychological trauma,'' Dr. <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Schonberg </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adolescence </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday Doctors should avoid `` accusatory questioning, -LRB- or -RRB- forcing testing on somebody who really does n't want to be tested; that becomes another assault,'' he said. `` One has to find a sensitive balance between the need to accumulate evidence and the need to protect the young person from yet another assault,'' he said. Immediately after the assault `` might not be the best time to do an internal examination,'' he said. `` It still does occur, that young people ... are dealt with insensitively and their medical contact therefore is not helpful to them,'' said <PERSON> Schonberg </PERSON>, director of the division of adolescent medicine at <ORGANIZATION> Montefiore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Citing <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> figures, <PERSON> Schonberg </PERSON> said nearly 50 percent of rape victims are young people under the age of 21. `` We would urge that every pediatric training program'' include instruction in how to deal with the emotional and physical problems associated with rape, he said. `` Most pediatricians have had little prior experience or training in managing such problems,'' members of the committee wrote in the journal. `` Residency and continued medical education programs should assist the pediatrician in developing the necessary skills and techniques for treating these patients in a sensitive and supportive manner.'' The article included a sample sexual assault data sheet that is widely available to pediatricians, with guidelines on what an exam of a rape victim should include. It urged discretion in the use of pregnancy prevention drugs, noting that they can produce nausea, vomiting and other side effects that could add to the victim's trauma. `` The incidence of pregnancy after rape is extremely low ... so the wisdom of using these drugs is questionable,'' the authors wrote. `` The practioner who chooses to use those drugs should be fully informed about these factors and should share these facts with patients.'' <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Birch </PERSON>, legislative counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Child </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said he advocates better training for physicians and others who deal with victimized youths. `` I think generally there's a feeling that professionals _ whether they're physicians, or attorneys or teachers _ whose jobs bring them into contact with children, are not prepared to deal with the kinds of situations that children find themselves in, where are they are victimized,'' he said by telephone Tuesday from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` Unfortunately, these professionals are the ones in our communities who have the contact with the children that should require them to be the best prepared,'' he said. `` I think that it may be a factor of our educational system, that has not recognized the extent to which children are victims of abuse or exploitation,'' <PERSON> Birch </PERSON> said, `` because certainly it's only been in the last 15 to 20 years that social services and medical professionals have even been able to identify the numbers of children who are victims.''
