<HEAD>Amex Head Warns Another Crash Possible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The lack of political progress toward substantially cutting the budget deficit and reforming federal market regulation threatens to cause another stock crash, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. `` The conditions that created the atmosphere in which a market meltdown nearly occurred are still present _ creating a kind of economic time bomb that threatens the whole system,'' <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> luncheon. <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said the budget deficit `` has not been satisfactorily addressed,'' and he complained that `` regulatory solutions ... have been debated but not enacted.'' However, he declined to single out either <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> or the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for blame. Both are about equally responsible for failure to reduce the budget deficit, he said. On regulatory reform, <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is hampered by committees `` jockeying for jurisdictional control.'' And, he said, although the administration has spent the past seven years trying to reduce regulation, it must now recognize `` the protection of the public must be the foremost consideration.'' `` If the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the administration continue to be paralyzed in a political deadlock ... I have great concerns about the future of the markets as we know them,'' he said. <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> called for the creation of a special study commission that, without delaying congressional and administration efforts at finding short-term solutions, would focus on reform for the next decade. <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON>, who heads the third-largest stock trading system in the nation, ranking behind the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the over-the-counter market, also said the securities industry must move to reform itself before individual investors return to the market in force. He said the current system for recruiting, training and paying brokers has made the public suspicious of brokers. He said brokerage firms should stop raiding each others' staffs, a practice he called `` demeaning piracy,'' and instead spend more to train brokers. The current commission system of compensation encourages brokers to make as many trades as they can and `` raises customers' fears that their brokers are doing business when the best strategy might be to sit tight,'' <PERSON> Levitt </PERSON> said. He suggested commissions based on an across-the-board percentage of assets managed rather than on the number of transactions.
