missing in action. <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON> is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nien </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government has done nothing since the war ended to help <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> recover from American bombing that destroyed thousands of schools, and has not aided <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s disabled veterans or the half-million orphans created by the conflict. He said it was `` unfortunate that -LRB- the agreement -RRB- was not fully implemented and it sometimes was wrongly interpreted. Both sides recognized the humanitarian issues of each other and both must be resolved.'' Wednesday's delivery is the fourth since the <PERSON> Vessey </PERSON> agreement. If <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> laboratories identify the 27 sets of remains, it would mean substantial progress because <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> has repatriated only 152 confirmed remains. The largest previous transfer _ Aug. 14, 1985 _ involved 26 remains, and at least 24 were confirmed. <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON> told <PERSON> Nien </PERSON> his constituents often say they believe <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> returns the remains gradually and still holds some living American prisoners. <PERSON> Nien </PERSON> called the charges `` unthinkable.'' <PERSON> Nguyen </PERSON> <PERSON> Can </PERSON>, head of the special Vietnamese office on resolving the MIA issue, denied charges that the skeletal remains of <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> pilot <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> were kept for years at a medical school or hospital before being returned to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Nov. 25. The <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATIO