<HEAD>Judge Won't Stay Order to Broaden Amnesty Standards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge on Tuesday refused to stay his order that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration broaden its standard for determining whether certain illegal aliens qualify for amnesty under the 1986 immigration law. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> denied the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s motion for a stay pending appeal of his ruling that overturned a regulation for processing amnesty requests from aliens who had legally entered the country but overstayed tourist or student visas. The regulation, which <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> said violated the plain language of the immigration law, required that the illegal status of non-immigrant aliens be known to the Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> as of Jan. 1, 1982 for them to qualify for amnesty. <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON> said the law merely required that any federal agency have documentation, such as a tax or Social Security form, from which officials could conclude an alien's status was illegal as of that date. Groups that counsel illegal aliens who brought the suit estimated that as many as 50,000 non-immigrant aliens were being denied legalization under the disputed regulations. More than 1 million illegal aliens have sought naturalization under the amnesty program that expires May 4. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is considering legislation to extend the deadline by six months. <PERSON> Sporkin </PERSON>, who had issued a preliminary injunction last week, made the ruling permanent.
