<HEAD>Homeowners Would Pay More for Natural Gas if Pipeline Policy
Changed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residential natural gas rates will increase if interstate pipelines are permitted to serve large industrial users directly, a group of gas distribution companies and others said Tuesday. An industry organization, the <ORGANIZATION> Process </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, disputed the claim. The distribution group, led by <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Distributors </ORGANIZATION>, an East Coast trade association, presented the summary of a study of 14 unidentified gas distribution companies. The summary said that if all industrial customers on 13 of these systems who could be served directly by interstate pipelines were to shift to the pipelines, rates to other customers would have to rise by 1 percent to 21 percent. The median rate increase was 5.7 percent. The increases would occur because the fixed cost of the distribution system would be spread over a smaller number of customers. An earlier study by the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> estimated that distribution companies could lose $ 2 billion in revenues if industrial customers could switch to direct service by the interstate pipelines. There are only a few such `` direct service'' customers now, often a factory that years ago chose to locate itself in an isolated area directly on a pipeline route, or was already there when the pipeline was built. The distribution group held a news conference to call attention to its support of a bill introduced last month by Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass. He wants to prevent the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> from approving so-called `` bypass'' service over the objections of state regulators. A <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> aide, <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurwit </PERSON>, said he introduced the bill because `` when large customers can get off the system and come back on at a later date, you do have some concerns that the remaining customers are paying more than their fair share.'' Rep. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharp </PERSON>, D-Ind., chairman of the subcommittee with jurisdiction over the bill, has said he does not want to deal with natural gas issues this year Nonetheless, <PERSON> Rufus </PERSON> <PERSON> McKinney </PERSON>, lobbyist for <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION>, said he was optimistic that backers could at least win hearings on the issue. <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Vlcek </PERSON>, counsel to the <ORGANIZATION> Process </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said his group opposed the <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> bill because, `` There is n't a great deal of confidence in public service commissions in a lot of states'' to protect industry, who, he said, often is paying more more than its share of distribution company costs. `` This is cast as industry vs. residential customers. I dispute that. There's a third party in these transactions, the shareholders of the distribution company,'' who, <PERSON> Vlcek </PERSON> said, were earning in some cases 16 percent to 17 percent on their investment.
</TEXT>
