<HEAD>Reagan Urges Nations To Sign Accord To Protect Ozone Layer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called on other nations Tuesday to ratify an international agreement to protect the stratospheric ozone layer from damaging chemicals. He made the plea in a statement announcing he had signed ratification documents in the wake of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s unanimous approval of the agreement March 14. `` But our action alone is not enough,'' the president said. `` The protocol enters into force next January only if at least 11 nations representing two-thirds of worldwide consumption of chlorofluorocarbons and halons ratify this agreement. `` Our immediate challenge, having come this far, is to promote prompt ratification by every signatory nation,'' he said. The agreement, signed in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, requires countries that are parties to reduce production and consumption of major ozone-depleting chemicals by 50 percent by 1999. Chlorofluorocarbons, which are used in refrigerants, cleaning fluids, foam products and _ except in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ aerosol sprays, destroy the high-altitude ozone layer that screens the Earth from harmful radiation.
