<HEAD>President Signs Food-for-Poor Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Tuesday signed legislation that gives the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> greater leeway to distribute surplus food commodities to poor nations. Under the amendments to the Agriculture Act of 1949, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> can now measure how much foodstuffs will be sent against available supplies, rather than having to meet a strict quota set forth in law. The law allows <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> to disburse these foodstuffs, `` subject to the availability of commodities.'' The legislation also requires the secretary to make private voluntary organizations, in addition to agencies of foreign governments, eligible to take part in the distribution of surplus food commodities. It imposes for the first time a 45-day deadline for the <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> to approve surplus food shipments. And it extends until 1990 a farmer-to-farmer program in which American farmers travel to foreign countries to give technical assistance.
