<HEAD>Soviet Permit Would Allow Afghan Communists to Evacuate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER C. PUTNAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is issuing evacuation permits for <ORGANIZATION> Afghan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and government officials to use if they must flee their country after a Soviet troop withdrawal, a human rights organization said Tuesday. The New York-based group, <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, released a copy of a blank 3-by-5-inch pass that it said was among 20 captured by Afghan Moslem guerrillas, who have battled the Afghan government and Soviet troops since 1979. <PERSON> Ludmilla </PERSON> <PERSON> Thorne </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> issued similar passes to South Vietnamese government officials when they were evacuated by air from <LOCATION> Saigon </LOCATION> in 1975 as the South Vietnamese capital fell to the communists. The copy of the Russian-language Afghan permit bears the emblem of a red star with a hammer and sickle and the words `` Permit for Special Evacuation.'' After the word `` Comrade,'' there is a blank line for the name of the card holder, followed by `` is granted the right for special evacuation by air and land transport, with the retention of all housing and food privileges after arrival at the new site.'' That is followed by a place for the signature of an `` authorized person'' and the date. The stamp of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Embassy </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> appears at the bottom. On the reverse side instructions in Pushtu, the Afghan language, inform the bearer that he can bring only one suitcase and no weapons or food. A map of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> attached to the document pinpoints two evacuation points, one near the Soviet Embassy. Earlier reports from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia