lict, now more than six years old. A senior administation official in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> with the vacationing president said conditions for regional talks have not been met. `` What we have right now is a truce, and cease-fire negotiations begin next week, and we're still working out the cease-fire zones. So the conditions are not yet present for regional discussions,'' said the official, who spoke only on condition of anonymity. `` Cease-fire discussions have to get started and we have to see some progress in those cease-fire discussions to make sure that they're not just discussions leading to a complete surrender of the freedom fighters and the total abandonment of their interests,'' the official added. <PERSON> Busby </PERSON> is making the trip just a week after taking over as special envoy, a post that had been vacant since Ambassador <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Habib </PERSON> stepped down last August because of an internal dispute over administration policy in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Busby </PERSON> has made several trips to the region since then while serving as principal deputy to Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Abrams </PERSON> decided that a full-time special envoy for <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was needed and <PERSON> Busby </PERSON> was assigned that duty, giving way to career diplomat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Kozak </PERSON> as principal deputy.
