<HEAD>TV May Help Racial Understanding, Howard Beach Study Suggests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A study at one <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> high school found that television may help break down racial and ethnic stereotypes, researchers said Tuesday. The study was conducted at a high school in the <LOCATION> Howard </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> section of <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>, which gained national attention as the site of a racially motivated killing in 1986. `` The good news is that the kids like the ethnic characters on television and they identify with them,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichter </PERSON>, a political scientist who conducted the study for the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>. `` The bad news is that they like the bad characters too.'' The survey found that black characters are the most popular on television, and that <PERSON> Cliff </PERSON> <PERSON> Huxtable </PERSON>, portrayed by <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Cosby </PERSON> in `` The Cosby Show,'' is the most popular character of all. Both Italian-American students and non-Italians said that Italian characters such as <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Micelli </PERSON> on `` Who's the Boss?'' were most typical of their ethnic group. Jewish students responded the least favorably to ethnic characters across the board, but also were the least likely to view them as realistic portrayals. In general, the study found that the more students liked television characters, the more likely they were to regard them as typical of their racial or ethnic group. <PERSON> Huxtable </PERSON> was one exception: although black students overwhelmingly regarded him as a typical black man, non-blacks were evenly split on whether he was typical. The choice of <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Adams </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN