<HEAD>Dust Bowl Conditions Developing In Nevada</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Above-average temperatures and below-average rainfall and snowpack are producing conditions in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> reminiscent of the dust bowl weather of the 1930s, state climatologist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> says. <PERSON> James </PERSON>, chairman of a newly formed governor's committee on drought, commented Tuesday as the panel met here to review weather information and discuss possible water conservation steps. <PERSON> James </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> had the driest February and March on record and has had only .02 inch of rain in more than 2 -LCB- months. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Weather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> representatives told the committee that snowpack in the <ORGANIZATION> Sierra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevadas </ORGANIZATION> is about 25-40 percent of normal and reservoirs in the in northern <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and eastern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> are at only half their average levels. Temperatures have run above normal in 12 of the past 14 months in <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> said, adding that such a pattern of high temperatures and lack of precipitation happened only once before in the state _ during the 1930s. State Engineer <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Morros </PERSON>, who oversees <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>'s groundwater resources, said he already has received reports of some shallow household wells in the Reno area and elsewhere starting to dry up.
