<HEAD>White-Band Disease Imperils Coral Reefs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s coral reefs are making a rapid recovery from a mysterious illness that bleached them white last summer, marine scientists say, but now those reefs are threatened by another potentially fatal disease. Dr. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaap </PERSON>, a researcher for the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>, said he's worried about the spread of white-band disease, which affects elkhorn coral, the branching type that's common on shallow reefs off the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION> <PERSON> Jaap </PERSON> said he has seen evidence of white-band disease off <LOCATION> Biscayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> and near the Grecian Rocks off Key Largo. The rocks are on the fringe of a coral reef sanctuary adjacent to <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennekamp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reef </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, a spectacular preserve that draws more than a million divers each year. `` In some cases off <LOCATION> Grecian </LOCATION> we were seeing entire colonies that had succumbed to it,'' <PERSON> Jaap </PERSON> said of the disease. He said white-band disease appears to be caused by a bacteria. <PERSON> Jaap </PERSON> said the disease could be getting a foothold in areas where coral has been weakened by turbid water, though that's not always the case. <PERSON> Jaap </PERSON> found evidence of white-band disease last month while surveying reefs to determine the extent of coral bleaching caused by another sometimes fatal affliction. The study, funded by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, covered reefs off <ORGANIZATION> Biscayne </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Key </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Largo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sanctuary </ORGANIZATION>, Looe Key National Marine Sanctuary and at the Eastern Dry Rocks off Key West. He said the coral has made a remarkable comeback from the bleaching illness. `` Only 1 to 2 percent were still severely bleached,'' <PERSON> Jaap </PERSON> said. `` They seem to be starting to regain their color. The reefs in the shallow waters are almost back to normal. I think that in another few weeks you'll see most of the coral completely back to normal.'' The bleaching disease struck coral last summer from the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>. Some experts believe the condition was caused by the unusually long period of high sea temperatures last summer, the hottest on record. The temperatures caused the dark algae covering the coral to disappear, whitening the coral. The coral eventually dies because the algae is its source of food. Areas killed by the bleaching phenomenon should restore themselves in two to three years. `` The cooler temperatures have had a beneficial effect. If they are given a reprieve this summer, they'll recover quite well,'' <PERSON> Jaap </PERSON> said.
