2 kilograms -LRB- about 906 pounds -RRB- of cocaine into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> through <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. The deal fell through when the people hired to fly the cocaine from <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s Haitian farm to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> stole the drugs, <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s henchmen have tried twice to kill him since then, including one attempt that occurred near the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> offices of the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON> is now under <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> protection and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> has been indicted for conspiracy in the case. Also indicted March 10 in the same case was his brother, <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON>, and Mrs. <PERSON> Delinois </PERSON>. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the subcommittee, noted that <PERSON> Quintana </PERSON>'s testimony shows `` yet another country ... polluting the streets of our country'' with drugs Previous testimony before the subcommittee has centered on Central and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> nations. Earlier, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> testified that marijuana was moved aboard planes as large as a DC-6, along with shrimp boats and _ on one occasion in 1983 _ a barge which carried 150 tons of the drug into a <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> port. Law enforcement officials were paid off `` when it had to be done,'' <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> said. Usually, they were given `` $ 50,000 or $ 60,000 to do nothing,'' he said. `` They were paid to look the other way.'' <PERSON> Vogel </PERSON> did not name any of the officials he said received payments. On one occasion in 1979 or 1980, <PERSON> Vogel </