<DATELINE>LAKE CHARLES, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Broadus </PERSON> <PERSON> Shearman </PERSON>, a publisher of the <ORGANIZATION> Lake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Charles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> who crusaded against gambling in the 1950s, has died. He was 94. <PERSON> Shearman </PERSON> died Monday at home after a long illness. As a result of his crusade against gambling in southwestern <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, he and four other newsmen were indicted by a special <LOCATION> Calcasieu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parish </LOCATION> grand jury on charges they defamed 16 public officials and three admitted gamblers. A special judge appointed to hear the case acquitted the newsmen, saying every allegation made in articles and editorials was without malice and was either true or could reasonably be believed to be true. With legislative help casinos and slot machines were eventually eliminated. In 1977, <PERSON> Shearman </PERSON> was cited in the National Better Newspaper Contest for community service for the newspaper's coverage of labor violence, stemming from a union attack on a construction site in which one man was killed and several people were injured. Legislators cited the newspaper's work as a key to getting the state's right-to-work law passed. <PERSON> Shearman </PERSON> was born June 27, 1893, in <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and entered the newspaper business as an advertising salesman for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> in 1914. He bought the Lake Charles paper in 1943 and acquired the <LOCATION> Roswell </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> -RRB- Daily Record in 1933 and the Hobbs -LRB- <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION> -RRB- Daily Sun and the <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION> -RRB- Chronicle News in 1936. <PERSON> Shearman </PERSON> also was active in the oil and gas business. He is survived by four children and a sister. One son, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Shearman </PERSON>, manages the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charles </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> papers. A grandson, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Shearman </PERSON>, is publisher at <LOCATION> Hobbs </LOCATION>. Although <PERSON> Shearman </PERSON> was no longer associated with the <LOCATION> Roswell </LOCATION> newspaper, a daughter, <PERSON> Marge </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON>, is married to <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Beck </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Roswell </LOCATION> publisher.
