<FIRST>r w AM-RecreationCommission     04-05 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Recreation Commission,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Closed Meetings of Recreation Commission Violated Law, GAO Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A presidential advisory commission on recreation held 34 closed meetings in violation of the law, congressional investigators said in a report released Tuesday. However, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report released by Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, also concluded that the violation `` may not have had a material impact on the commission's operations and its final report and recommendations.'' The commission chairman said he never realized so many minor get-togethers like informal lunches would count as `` meetings.'' The 15-member group in question, the President's Commission on Americans Outdoors, was organized in September 1985 under an executive order issued by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and made its report in December 1986. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report appeared to uphold many complaints by a group opposed to the commission's recommendations, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inholders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. An `` inholder'' is an owner of private property surrounded by public land, such as the owner of a home in a national park. A lawsuit filed by the group to overturn the report got nowhere when a judge ruled that it could not sue because it had failed to protest when the alleged violations were occuring. The commission was formed as a government advisory committee, which meant that it had to hold its meetings in public with a 15-day notice, a designated federal official had to attend each meeting and detailed minutes had to be kept. Permission had to be sought from the host agency head to close a meeting, and reasons for closing it had to be submitted. `` The -LRB- Interior -RRB- department committee management officer thought that responsibility for -LRB- the act's -RRB- requirements was being handled by the commission, but commission officials were unaware that such a transfer of responsibility had occured,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report said. As a result, and despite an extensive campaign to generate public advice, the commission published notices for only 18 of its 60 meetings, and only 10 were published in time; proper procedures for closing 34 of the 60 meetings were not followed; minutes were kept for only 27 of 60 meetings and the department employee designated to attend commission meetings attended only 11. <PERSON> Lamar </PERSON> <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON>, a former governor of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> who was chairman of the commission, said in written comments: `` I did not ever imagine that a ` meeting' could be a lunch among a few of the commission members where no decisions were reached or a staff working session which some commission memebrs briefly attended. If such an unusual definition of ` meeting' is what <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> really intended, then perhaps <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> officials could visit commissions like ours when they begin and say that.'' <PERSON> Rick </PERSON> <PERSON> Ventura </PERSON>, assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> for policy, budget and administration, wrote that the department was reviewing its procedures and would make sure that similar presidential commissions assigned to it would be served by staff familiar with the law. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Cushman </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inholders </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said the commission `` operated in a vacuum and made silly recommendations'' that it might not have made if the requirements had been met. But <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Crandall </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recreation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, a trade association, said <PERSON> Cushman </PERSON> `` could not be more wrong. ... We had an extraordinarily open process, and did nothing in camera.''
</TEXT>
