<HEAD>Cross-Country Trek Leaves Lorraine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Following two yellow farm horses temporarily dubbed mules, marchers in a cross-country pilgrimage for the poor stepped off Tuesday from the small motel where <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> died 20 years ago. `` We're trying to stir up the countryside. We're trying to bring people out to express their outrage about poverty,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>, a civil rights organization founded by King. The combination march and motorcade through <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> was scheduled to begin Monday following a memorial service on the 20th anniversary of King's death. The trek was delayed a day, however, because two mules that were to pull a farm wagon on the marching portions of the trip failed to arrive on time. The two animals trucked in for the trip Tuesday turned out to be small yellow work horses but were strapped up to the wagon as the procession got under way. `` Today, they're mules,'' <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said as he climbed aboard the wagon. <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> SCLC </ORGANIZATION> marches often use a mule-drawn wagon as a symbol of poverty. The 30 or so marchers walked about a mile and a half from The Lorraine before loading the wagon on a rental truck, putting the horses on a trailer and climbing aboard three vans for a trip to Marks, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, the first stop on the tour. The group plans to ride in the vans for the rural parts of the trip and stage marches and rallies at towns along the way. The pilgrimage is scheduled to arrive in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> on April 29. <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said his group will hold several public hearings on the trip for a report on poverty to be given to the Republican and Democratic parties at their conventions this summer. `` Most poor people are working people,'' he said. `` They simply do n't earn enough to carry them out of the pits of poverty.'' In recent years, particularly during President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s administration, the nation has lost the urgency it once felt to help the poor, <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said `` You're not going to get the private sector, where most jobs are, to respond until you get public policy that encourages them, that requires them and offers the incentives for them to provide job training and job opportunities for those who need it,'' he said. <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said the cross-country trek was begun at The Lorraine because King was assassinated there while helping the working poor by leading a strike by sanitation workers. `` We will not let any commemorative service for Dr. King end with a benediction,'' <PERSON> Lowery </PERSON> said. `` That's why we closed the April 4 event with a pilgrimage as part of the poor people's campaign.''
