<HEAD>U.S. Says Bases in Philippines Needed In Face Of Soviet Buildup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The American envoy at the opening of talks on the future of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases in the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> said Tuesday the facilities are needed in the face of a Soviet buildup. Ambassador <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said the six bases, where about 20,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel and defense workers are stationed, are critical to security in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. Many Filipinos have called for an end to the garrisons, which they see as a vestige of colonialism. <PERSON> Platt </PERSON> said that while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troop strength in the region has remained constant, the `` Soviet military presence has grown from an essentially zero base to one of substantial proportions.'' `` It only requires an overnight shift in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> intentions, given their current capability, to transform this presence into a serious economic and military threat to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and to the region,'' he added. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> officials are reviewing a 1947 agreement under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> operates the bases, the last major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military installations in <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. They technically are under command of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> but are effectively controlled by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. As the talks got under way at a seaside convention complex in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, about 500 people staged a peaceful march to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> protesting the bases. Eight imprisoned communist rebels issued a statement demanding the bases be closed. The government has been fighting a 19-year war against communist guerrillas. Spokesme