<HEAD>Laughing Gunmen in Massacre of 28 Yelled ``Kill Everyone You
Can!''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Please note language in 23rd graf, ``Then you ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gunmen laughed and screamed `` Kill everyone you can!'' as they massacred 28 villagers at a rural Easter festival, newspapers in the capital reported Tuesday. The hooded killers shot dead an elderly, one-legged man as he struggled to get on the donkey and flee, the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> daily <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tiempo </ORGANIZATION> quoted an unidentified survivor as saying. A 10-year-old boy, <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sierra </PERSON>, who was among those ordered to lie face down in the dirt and not look up, was shot in the head at point-blank range by one of the killers when he lifted his head, another survivor was quoted as telling an <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tiempo </LOCATION> reporter. One other child, a 14-year-old boy, was also killed in the Sunday bloodbath. There were conflicting reports on the number of wounded, ranging from 10 to 15. A death toll of 33 given Monday was revised downward to 28 Tuesday by Gov. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabriel </PERSON> <PERSON> Amin </PERSON> <PERSON> Manzur </PERSON> of northwest <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> state. The governor said police and the army suspect the massacre was the work of leftist guerrillas, <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiempo </PERSON> said. However, the murders had all the earmarks of the work of a right-wing death squad. <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiempo </PERSON> and another <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> daily, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Espectador </LOCATION>, sent reporters to the scene, a thatched roof hut in remote mountains where about 200 people were celebrating the end of Holy Week. The area, know as <LOCATION> Mejor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Esquina </LOCATION>, lies 280 miles west of the capital city of <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> and has about 50 families, with no house closer than 1,500 feet to its neighbor. Here is what happened, according to the accounts given reporters: The traditional partying started Saturday afternoon, with an eight-piece band of guitars and accordions playing the songs dear to Colombian peasants _ ballads of hard-working cowboys, lost love and happiness amid poverty A pig was slaughtered for the feast and chickens were killed. Sunday started off with horse races. In the afternoon there was a dance for the children in the small farmhouse made of mud bricks. Women cooked stew in huge pots throughout the afternoon and the men drank beer and aguardiente, a Colombian liquor with a faint taste of licorice. In the evening, the peasants danced and shouted to each other over music blaring from large speakers. Only a few noticed vehicles park about 150 feet away with lights out. Some people said there were about 10 gunmen. Others said there were as many as 20. Some said they wore military jungle clothing. Others said they wore police uniforms. One thing all survivors agreed on was the gunmen laughing crazily as they fired repeatedly into the crowd amid shouts, screams, the hysterical crying of children. Some people ran into the hut, and gunmen followed, firing as they entered. <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Llorente </PERSON> said he survived because the bodies of dead friends lay atop him as the killers fired into the room. No one in the band was killed. One gunman smashed an accordion and whacked the musician across his backside with the flat part of a 2-foot-long machete. The shooting lasted about 20 minutes and the gunmen became more selective in choosing victims. Eight people were shot in the back of the head as they lay face down in the hut. The gunmen left, warning survivors to keep their faces in the dirt for five minutes. `` Then you can look up and cry over what you find, you sons of bitches!'' one attacker shouted. That is when the 10-year-old boy was shot for lifting his head. The sound of the vehicles died out and the village was filled with the groans of the wounded, cries of people calling for loved ones, the agonized whinnying of injured horses. The next day, in nearby <LOCATION> Planeta </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, someone painted on a wall, `` The Magnificient Ones are here to clean things up.'' There are a dozen right-wing death squads in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> with names like the Vampires and the Crickets. This the first time the Magnificient Ones had been heard of. Death squads have killed about 600 people in the last three years. The left says the army is behind killings. The army denies it. The government says it has been unable to find out who organizes the death squads. So far no one from any death squad has been caught. Leftist guerrillas draw combatants from rural areas, and <ORGANIZATION> Mejor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Esquina </ORGANIZATION> may have been one of them. At the school, a guerrilla slogan _ Long live the <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> _ has been painted near the entrance. The schoolmaster, <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Berrios </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilches </PERSON>, was among those killed.
</TEXT>
