<HEAD>Gorbachev Condemns Foreign Interference In Ethnic Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> lashed out Tuesday at foreigners he said were trying to aggravate an ethnic dispute in the southern <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION>. `` They are trying to interfere in our internal affairs, to exacerbate problems from the outside and -LRB- are -RRB- engaging in provocations,'' he said. `` At present this is particularly visible in connection with the events around <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>.'' His comments were similar to recent remarks in the official press condemning purported outside interference in the dispute over <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, a region in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> that Armenians want attached to their republic. The Soviet leader's remarks came at a <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> meeting with <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and a former chancellor of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported on the meeting. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> singled out broadcasters for criticism. `` Various radio stations, including official ones, have joined in the subversive activity,'' he said. `` Especially active ... is <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Welle </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- West German radio -RRB-.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> did not say how the radio stations were purportedly being subversive, but other Soviet reports have accused Western journalists of sharpening tensions between Armenians and Azeris, the dominant ethnic group in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> told <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON>, `` We will handle problems that have accumulated, including on the nationalities issue, within the framework of the democratic process we have firmly chosen.'' Soviet newspapers reported Tuesday that four businesses have gone bankrupt in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION>, the main city of <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, because of a strike but that workers have been returning to their jobs in increasing numbers. The first reports that workers were returning to their jobs came Friday. The government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday that workers were continuing to go back to work to their jobs because of repeated appeals by Communist authorities. Workers began striking in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> on March 24 to protest government refusal to turn the city and the surrounding region, <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, over to the Armenian republic. Most of the region's 160,000 residents are ethnic Armenians but since 1923 it has been part of the neighboring republic of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. The Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, the national parliament, announced a plan on March 23 for $ 690 million in economic, social and culture improvements for <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, which some Armenians say has suffered under the control of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> said that in <LOCATION> Stepanakert </LOCATION> on Tuesday, all workers of the building materials plant showed up as did more than half of the employees of the electrical engineering works and silk mill. About a third of the workers of the shoe and furniture factories reported for work, it said. The annexation issue touched off demonstrations and strikes in <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> on Feb. 13, and the unrest spread to the Armenian captial, <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>. The dispute led to ethnic rioting Feb. 28 in the Azerbaijani city of <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION> that left at least 32 people dead.
