<HEAD>Jury Deliberates Complicated Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL SIMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury deliberated a second day Tuesday without deciding the fate of 13 people, nine of them accused of conspiring to violently overthrow the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and establish an Aryan nation. At midafternoon, the jury asked <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> for a trial transcript. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> sent jurors a note saying a transcript would be about 7,000 pages and would not be ready for three or four months. He told jurors that recordings of long portions of testimony could not be played for them and they should rely on their memory and notes. The jury was to resume deliberations Wednesday. The case went to the jury on Monday, after a trial that began Feb. 16 and included 192 witnesses. Defendant <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday that the trial is a move by the government to snuff out views that do not meet its approval. He said he expects to be acquitted, but added, `` In any case, they win _ they break us financially.'' <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> and defendants <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miles </PERSON> and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Beam </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> are considered among the leaders of the white-supremacist movement in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. One of <PERSON> Beam </PERSON>'s lawyers, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON>, said acquittal would slow the movement more than a guilty verdict because it would show that white supremacists `` can get a fair trial in American courts. If acquittal comes back in this case, it will go a long way toward neutralizing the right wing. If they're convicted, the right wing will think they've been shanghaied.'' Besides the nine people accused of seditious conspiracy, which carries a maximum of 20 years in prison and a $ 20,000 fine, five defendants are accused of conspiring to kill federal officials and two of transporting stolen money across state lines. The murder plot could be punished by life imprisonment; the transporting charge by a term of 10 years plus a $ 10,000 fine. A key government witness was <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON>, who is serving 20 years for racketeering. He led a white-supremacist group named the Covenant, the Sword and the Arm of the Lord. His group carried out bombings in furtherance of a conspiracy, he testified, that was made in July 1983 at <LOCATION> Hayden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, at a convocation of <PERSON> Butler </PERSON>'s group, the <ORGANIZATION> Aryan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>. Defendants at that meeting have said that there was no conspiracy and that <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON> made up the story in hopes of getting a sentence reduction.
