sighting false. Picks up 7th graf pvs, ``Earlier a.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOUNDSVILLE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The search for three killers who escaped from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> Penitentiary focused for hours Tuesday on what turned out to be a false sighting at a restaurant, state police said. `` At first check, it seemed to be them,'' said state police Sgt. D.E. <PERSON> Cook </PERSON>. `` But after further checks, we could n't make a positive I.D. `` We retraced all the people who saw them. They were n't the three,'' <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> said, adding that the investigative effort had taken six hours. State police had said four workers at a fast food restaurant in Cross Lanes, 11 miles west of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> and about 170 miles south of the prison, had made a positive identification of the escapees based on mug shots. Convicted murderers <PERSON> Bobby </PERSON> <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tommie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mollohan </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> used stolen bolt cutters in their Sunday night escape from the <LOCATION> Moundsville </LOCATION> prison. Earlier, a prison official blamed the escape on antiquated facilities and the need to use inmate labor. Corrections Commissioner A.V. <PERSON> Dodrill </PERSON> said at least one of the escapees was probably familiar with `` every nook and cranny'' of the 122-year-old prison, which <PERSON> Dodrill </PERSON> says can be kept running only with the help of the inmates. As a result, he said, inmates often become familiar with the institution's weaknesses. `` This prison is in terrible shape. The plumbing is especially bad. It needs constant renovation,'' <PERSON> Dodrill </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Mollohan </PERSON>, 45, was convicted of robbing and killing a grocer in 1973. At the time, <PERSON> Mollohan </PERSON> had escaped from a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> prison and also was wanted in <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> on armed robbery charges. `` <PERSON> Mollohan </PERSON> was the ringleader,'' <PERSON> Dodrill </PERSON> said. `` He is an excellent plumber and probably knew every nook and cranny.'' <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON>, 35, was convicted of killing one police officer and accused of shooting another. Authorities said he had sworn revenge on those who had put him behind bars. Police have assigned protection to those who helped convict <PERSON> Stacy </PERSON>, including the judge in his case and a <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, woman who testified against him. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 28, was serving a life sentence for felony murder, arson and robbery. <PERSON> Dodrill </PERSON> said authorities are trying to determine whether the three were aided in their escape by correctional officers. `` That possibility does exist,'' the commissioner said. The last escape from <LOCATION> Moundsville </LOCATION> was in February 1983, when two inmates climbed over a wall behind the prison. They were recaptured within 24 hours. In 1979, 15 inmates, including convicted cop killer <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, escaped from the massive, stone block prison, killing an off-duty state trooper who was driving past. All 15 eventually were recaptured.
