<HEAD>Pravda Editorial Condemns Stalinism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-8 UPDATE with Gorbachev comments. Pick up 6th
graf pvs, Pravda's editors ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda on Tuesday denounced Soviets who are nostalgic for dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s rule and say <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms are damaging socialism Pravda also lashed out at publications that praise Stalinism and said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s `` glasnost'' policy of more openness on some issues does not include criticizing principles of the economic reforms the Soviet leader calls `` perestroika.'' `` We need disputes helping to advance perestroika and leading to the consolidation of forces and cohesion around perestroika rather than to disunity,'' Pravda said in a full-page, unsigned editorial. It said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> needs people dedicated to improving housing, food supplies and services rather than those obsessed with uncovering suspected enemies of socialism. `` A patriot is not he who cries out loudly about an alleged ` internal threat' to socialism, who, joining with a few political extremists, seeks internal enemies everywhere,'' Pravda said. `` A patriot is he who acts in the interest of the country, of the people, without fear of any difficulty.'' In a <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> meeting Tuesday with <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON>, the head of <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and former chancellor of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> acknowledged that his reforms have generated controversy. The official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency quoted <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, as saying, `` There are people who think everything is collapsing. Just as in the beginning of this century ` matter vanished' in the perceptions of some people as a result of new discoveries in physics, now it seems to some that socialism is vanishing.'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said that what is really happening is that socialism `` is ridding itself of everything that had deformed it in the past and is demonstrating tremendous dynamism, the wealth of its social and humanistic content.'' Pravda's editors said they felt compelled to address the issue of Stalinism because another newspaper had raised it improperly. <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION>, official daily of the Russian republic's party and government, carried a letter from a <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> teacher who defended <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> It was published March 13, just before <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> left for <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> and his chief of propaganda, <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yavovlev </PERSON>, went to <LOCATION> Mongolia </LOCATION>. In the past year, Soviet publications have criticized the excesses of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who ruled for three decades and died in 1953. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in November the dictator's guilt for the purges in which millions died was `` enormous and unforgivable,'' but defended <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s policies of rapid industrialization and collectivizating of agriculture. The Pravda editorial appeared to be an attempt to draw the party line on Stalinism. It repeated criticisms of <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> but said <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s opponents wo n't let the issue rest, either because they feel more comfortable with <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s repression or because it would serve their own interests. `` In one person this may be directed at taking more and giving less, in another in wrapping in respectable clothes their efforts to claim a monopoly in science, personal innocence or something else,'' the paper said. Pravda criticized the system under <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> as `` thoughtless execution of orders and suppression of initiative.'' The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> can not hide from the fact that `` many thousands'' of party workers, economic and military officials, scientists and cultural figures were exiled or killed, it said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> launched his effort to restructure Soviet society three years ago, and Pravda said there are those who feel widespread changes could undermine the Soviet system. `` Not all realize fully that the administrative-command methods have exhausted themselves,'' it said. `` All who pin hopes on those methods or their modifications would do well to wake up to the fact that we have had that more than once, but it did not bring about the desired results.'' People should `` get rid of the nostalgia for the past, when some people said things and others were supposed to heed and uncomplainingly fulfill the orders,'' Pravda advised. It said statements in the letter published by <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> are `` an attempt, little by little, to revise party decisions.'' `` At meetings at the party <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> it has been said more than once that the Soviet press is not a private shop and that the Communists writing in the press and the editors should be aware of their responsibility for the articles and the publications,'' it declared. `` In this case the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION>, which has.. done much for perestroika, has departed from this principle.''
