<HEAD>World's Tallest Woman Honored At Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANK LOWENKRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A middle school music instructor was singing a sweet tune Tuesday after finding the right measures for a chair to fit <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, the world's tallest woman. The chair was one of many gifts the 7-foot-7 \ <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> received at a party in her honor `` It is our way of showing appreciation for the way she faced challenges to make something of her life,'' said <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Prime </PERSON>, a longtime friend of <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s who coordinated the `` High on Life'' party. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, 32, is recognized as the world's tallest woman by the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>. More than 150 groups and people became involved in the project to honor <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>. The $ 8,500 in gifts included clothing, a quilt and a leather handbag. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Penwell </PERSON> estimated he spent 20 hours building the wooden, upholstered chair, which <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> sat on for the first time Tuesday. `` I decided to make the chair when my wife became involved in the project and we realized that <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> had special needs besides clothing,'' he said. `` Designing furniture is my hobby. `` I knew how tall <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> was and I estimated what size the chair should be,'' he said. `` The top of the chair is 56 inches high and the seat is 24 inches wide. The seat is 28 inches off the ground and 28 inches deep.'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the chair was very comfortable. `` This day is just incredible. I ca n't believe how much this thing snowballed,'' <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said. `` It's nice to know that there are people here who think so much about me.'' The gifts are the latest in a series of special events for <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, who decided to leave her job last year at a <LOCATION> Canadian </LOCATION> museum and return to <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. She once lived in <LOCATION> Shelbyville </LOCATION>, southeast of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. She started work in February as a secretary-receptionist in Mayor <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudnut </PERSON>'s office. `` When I heard she types 93 words per minute, I decided we should get her,'' <PERSON> Elena </PERSON> <PERSON> Leigh-Cohen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s supervisor, said. `` We've had to make some adjustments in the office, like raising her desk, and we're going to have a special chair made.''
