<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 16-year-old boy on Tuesday pleaded guilty as an adult to second-degree murder in the death of an 86-year-old man during a robbery for a jar of pennies. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Schrom </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, one of two 16-year-olds accused of fatally stabbing <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Linard </PERSON> <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> in January, entered the plea in <LOCATION> Mower </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION>. Attorneys for both sides presented Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kimball </PERSON> with a proposal under which <PERSON> Schrom </PERSON>, who was charged with first-degree murder in juvenile court, would plead guilty to second-degree murder in adult court. The other teen-ager, charged in juvenile court with first-degree murder, remains in custody in lieu of $ 100,000 bond. A hearing is scheduled next week, but County Attorney <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> has said she does not expect a plea agreement in his case. Sheriff <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> has said the boys took a few dollars in pennies from <PERSON> Fink </PERSON>'s home. The boys knew <PERSON> Fink </PERSON> and were invited into his home, the sheriff said.
