<HEAD>Moslems and Christians Join in General Strike for Wage Increases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Feuding Moslems and Christians joined in a nationwide strike Tuesday to demand 300 percent wage increases to counter inflation and the economic chaos brought on by 13 years of civil war. In southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, rival Moslem factions engaged in a gun battle that left one man killed and four wounded. Police said the fight near the town of <LOCATION> Nabatiyeh </LOCATION> was between the Syrian-backed <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> militia and the pro-Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. They said Amal militiamen had raided several villages and rounded up 10 <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> members in a search for gunmen who fired at the car of <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION>'s militia commander in <LOCATION> Nabatiyeh </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Mahmoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Faqih </PERSON>, on Monday. Police said <PERSON> Faqih </PERSON> was not in the car at the time. The one-day general strike was the latest in a series of demonstrations that began nearly two years ago to protest the economic situation. Banks, schools, shops, gasoline stations, government offices and other businesses closed in both Christian east <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and cities and towns throughout the country. But some Lebanese were sceptical. `` We've tried this before and nothing happened,'' said <PERSON> Adel </PERSON> <PERSON> Bohsali </PERSON>, an employee at a pastry shop in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The General Confederation of <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unions </ORGANIZATION>, which claims 300,000 members, said <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> airport, hospitals, pharmacies, bakeries and newspapers were exempt from the strike. In 1975, when the civil war began, the annual inflation rate was 9 percent. It is now 225 percent. The Lebanese pound, once the soundest currency in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, exchanged at 2.5 to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar before the civil war and the rate last week was 360 per dollar. The pound's collapse sent prices soaring in a country that imports more than 85 percent of its needs. In its strike call, the labor confederatin said Tuesday's action was a warning and an indefinite work stoppage would begin April 15 if the demand for the 300 percent increase, retroactive to January, was not met. A government source, speaking with the condition he not be identified, said Cabinet ministers were considering a compromise that would approve wage increases but they would be limited to 100 percent.
