<HEAD>Official Denies China Reducing Number Of Overseas Students</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An education official on Tuesday denied reports that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will drastically reduce the number of students it allows to study overseas, especially in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> <PERSON> Xinbai </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> who is in charge of Chinese students abroad, called the reports groundless, the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> reported. It quoted <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> as saying <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has a long-standing policy of sending students abroad and the policy had not changed and `` will never change.'' He said the numbers of both state-financed and privately financed students were expected to stay the same. According to <PERSON> Huang </PERSON>, the government has sent about 3,000 students abroad each year since 1980. The number sent by their employers or by academic institutions has increased steadily and in 1987 topped 5,000, he said. <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> estimated that an additional 3,000 students are financing their own overseas education. Since <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> began sending students overseas in 1979 as part of its general opening to the outside world, more than 40,000 state-funded students have gone to study in 70 countries, <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> said according to <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> last summer announced new regulations tightening controls on students going abroad and said they must be `` ideologically and morally sound.'' Many of the students have not returned home because of better jobs and living conditions overseas. <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> said 20,000 students have completed their studies abroad and returned to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Of the other 20,000 state-funded students still overseas, 10,000 are studying in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he said. News reports said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has 27,000 Chinese students, 10,000 paying their own way and 7,000 on scholarships. Some students who returned from abroad have said their skills and knowledge are not put to full use in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, and they have trouble readjusting to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s rigid political and social norms. Recent Western news reports said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> changed its overseas study policy, cutting the number of students going abroad to 3,000. Some reports said only 600 new students would be allowed to go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> because <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> was concerned that students were becoming too Americanized and were bringing back capitalist and bourgeois attitudes. `` It is utterly groundless to say that the numbers of students to be sent abroad, particularly those sent to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, shall be cut substantially,'' <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> said. He said 4,600 state-funded students would be sent to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this year. But <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> reported <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> said some adjustments were made in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s study-abroad program. Under the new guidelines, students in applied fields of study are more likely to be sent overseas, and more students will be sent to countries where there are few Chinese students already studying. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> also will cut back the number of undergraduate and graduate students going overseas and send abroad more scholars engaged in advanced research, <PERSON> Huang </PERSON> said.
