pvs bgng ``We're seeing...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> narrowly lost the votes of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s blue collar workers to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and attracted only a quarter of the white vote, exit polls said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> drew huge crowds at strike sites and hard-pressed manufacturing communities in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, but that enthusiasm did not translate into primary votes. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> beat <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> solidly among white blue collar workers and edged him in that category with blacks included, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won 41 percent of blue collar Democratic voters, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> said, to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s 37 percent. Among white blue-collar voters only, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had 47 percent, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> 27 percent. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s numbers were similar, with 43 percent of the overall blue collar vote going for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and 37 percent for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. As in previous contests, the black vote went overwhelmingly for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. Among whites, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> won 23 percent support while <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> put the figure slightly higher at 28 percent. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> won just 7 percent of the white vote in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> in 1984. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> polls said he won 22 percent in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> last week and 32 percent in liberal <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> on March 1. Said <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> poll analyst <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Muzzio </PERSON>: `` We may be looking at his ceiling here.'' `` We're seeing a dual electorate: a 