<HEAD>Opposition Paper Suspends Publication, Has No Newsprint</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: La Prensa suspends publication indefinitely, new info-changes
grafs 1-7. Pick up 4th pvs: The Ministry of Industry...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s only opposition newspaper, suspended publication indefinitely Tuesday saying the Sandinista government had not provided newsprint. A front-page story said `` with this edition we exhaust our supply of paper, so we will not be able to circulate as long as the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government, the only supplier, does n't sell us paper.'' Anti-Sandinista rebels have charged that the government, by not providing newsprint, violated a recent promise to allow a free press. Tuesday's <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> article rejected government suggestions that <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> ran out of newsprint because of mismanagement of its limited supply, saying publishers had reduced the daily's size from 12 to 8 pages and taken other steps to conserve. Deputy publisher <PERSON> Cristiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON> said earlier Tuesday: `` We have no paper to come out tomorrow, or on the following days, because the government claims there is no newsprint in the country, but we know there is.'' In a telephone interview, she noted the country's two other daily newspapers, the official <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> publication Barricada and pro-government <PERSON> Nuevo </PERSON> <PERSON> Diario </PERSON>, `` have been coming out normally with eight full pages.'' Barricada and <ORGANIZATION> Nuevo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diario </ORGANIZATION> are morning papers and <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prensa </LOCATION> is an afternoon daily. The <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement it could not solve <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>'s problem because a shipment of newsprint scheduled to arrive in March had not reached <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION