<HEAD>Undercover Agents to Check on Courtesy in Singapore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government plans to hire undercover courtesy agents to root out rudeness among civil servants. The latest twist in a 10-year campaign to make Singaporeans mind their manners will see private investigators snooping at counters in government buildings where the public is served. Seven research and public relations agencies have bid for a contract to measure courtesy in the civil service, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Tan </PERSON>, deputy director of the Psychological Defense Division of the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> and Information. A private company is sought for the job to `` ensure objectivity in the exercise,'' <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Straits </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. The courtesy `` audit'' is not a witch hunt to pinpoint individuals, he said. Its purpose is to investigate causes of rudeness and see what can be done to correct them. `` Systems which do n't allow people to be flexible can affect their behavior or cause others to think they are rude.'' <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> said. The first part of the survey will attempt to rank government ministries and statutory bodies in terms of their impact on peoples's lives. `` Civil servants work under constraints,'' <PERSON> Tan </PERSON> said. `` Customers may demand that they bypass the system and when they do n't, it comes across as rudeness.'' The check on government workers who deal with the public is in addition to the annual nationwide courtesy drive. Banners and signs, a `` courtesy hotline,'' television announcements and lapel badges appear each July to drive the message home. `` Courtesy: It Makes Life Better,'' is the slogan for 1988. The courtesy campaign is only one of a long series of official efforts to raise civic consciousness in <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>. Unlike most of the others, such as the anti-littering and do n't jaywalk drives, the discourteous are not threatened with fines. Public concern about rudeness started in 1978 when the <ORGANIZATION> Tourist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Promotion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> urged those who dealt with visitors to be polite so they would spend more. `` Courtesy Is Our Way Of Life,'' was the original slogan. `` Make Courtesy Our Way Of Life'' was adopted the following year, when Prime Minister <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yew </PERSON> got involved in national etiquette. `` To be courteous to free-spending tourists and to be rude to fellow Singaporeans is to demean ourselves,'' he said. `` Then we become a despicable people, moved only by the thought of profit.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> set 1990 as the deadline to `` file down the ragged corners of our social behavior which can grate on each other.'' The year 1990 was chosen because by then more than 75 percent of the city-state's 2.6 million people will be living in government-built apartments. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said neighbors would likely be lifelong ones and everone would have a stake in smooth relations. Courtesy campaigners confirm that much remains to be done to polish what is called `` social responsibility'' for public housing, parks and toilets. Many apartment blocks have become high-rise slums with elevators reeking of urine and corridors filled with trash. The elevator problem is so bad that the <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> installed a sophisticated monitoring system in three buildings. Sensors activated by the high salt content in urine stop the elevator, activate a video camera in the ceiling and alert the janitor. Officials said five male culprits, aged 7 to 79, have been caught so far this year. `` Singaporeans may not be the most discourteous people on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> but they are certainly nowhere near the top 10 when it comes to courtesy,'' said then-Second Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Sinnathamby </PERSON> <PERSON> Rajaratnam </PERSON> when he inaugurated the 1983 campaign.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs April 12</NOTE>
