<HEAD>Benazir Bhutto's Pakistan Opposition is in Disarray</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, political foe of President <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>, is still queen of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s political opposition, but she reigns over a party in disarray The <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> People's Party -LRB- PPP -RRB-, which she inherited from her late father, Prime Minister <PERSON> Zulfikar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, has been racked in recent months by political infighting, an ideological shift and a poor showing in local elections. Nevertheless, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> says she is determined to pull her grass-roots movement back together for national elections scheduled for 1990 in which she could face <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> head-on. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> has indicated he will run. Millions turned out in April 1986 when Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, now 34, returned from two years of voluntary exile in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The adoring masses likened her to the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>' <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> who would ride to office on a wave of `` people power.'' Two years later, however, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s critics say her policies are hard to discern from those of the <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> government. They call her leadership autocratic, her lifestyle patrician, and claim her overtures toward the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> run counter to the <ORGANIZATION> PPP </ORGANIZATION>'s traditions <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> overthrew her father in a 1977 military coup. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> later was convicted of complicity in the killing of a political opponent and he was hanged in 1979. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>, an army general and chief of the army staff, ruled by martial law until the end of 1985, when a civilian government was voted into office in an election that barred political parties. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> retained the presidency. Since then, <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> and his prime minister, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON> <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON>, have restored a number of fundamental civil rights and lifted most censorship of the press. In an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> attributed the recent criticism of her to the government. `` In the first years of overmilitary rule, the name of the <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> family was not allowed to appear in the press,'' she said. `` The new target, since the last two years, is to flood newspapers with stories on <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> and flood them with distorted stories attacking my capabilities, attacking my leadership.'' But many of her critics are current and former <ORGANIZATION> PPP </ORGANIZATION> members. `` Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> is a complete mistress unto herself, seldom considering it necessary to consult the -LRB- party's -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on major issues,'' wrote <ORGANIZATION> PPP </ORGANIZATION> member <PERSON> Ayaz </PERSON> <PERSON> Amir </PERSON> in The <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, a Pakistani magazine. The critics say the <ORGANIZATION> PPP </ORGANIZATION> is still a party of the <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> family, built around the charisma of <PERSON> Zulfikar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and perpetuated by what followers view as his martyrdom. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> takes more seriously the criticism of her changing policies, especially her pro-Americanism and her shift away from her father's socialist ideals. `` <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is in a period of transition,'' she said. `` We do n't have a direct military rule; we have an indirect military rule, or we have the iron fist in the velvet glove In this new situation the party and the party workers must also make the mental transition and the necessary adjustments that come from conforming to the new circumstances.'' She said her warming toward the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which she once accused of helping cause her father's downfall, is a pragmatic recognition of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s role in the region. `` It is a country that gives tremendous economic and military aid to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. One can not ignore that reality.'' Along with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s government, her party supports the Moslem resistance against the Soviet-backed government in neighboring <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. As for her economic policies, which are described as moderate, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> said she has deviated no more from the <ORGANIZATION> PPP </ORGANIZATION>'s founding principles than her father did. `` This is nothing new. They -LRB- the left wing -RRB- would like to transform the <ORGANIZATION> PPP </ORGANIZATION>, which is a populist, social-democratic party in the Moslem context, into a Marxist party,'' she said. `` We may not agree, but -LRB- we -RRB- respect them for having their views and expect them to respect our views.'' Upon her triumphal return to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> in 1986, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> called for elections within months but the demand was not met. She then called for mass protests on July 5 of that year, the anniversary of <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s coup, and the turnout was far less than expected. The following month, she and 400 opposition leaders were arrested for defying a government ban on rallies. She was released, but her problems were compounded this past November when her party won only 20 percent of some 75,000 seats at stake in local elections. Although candidates officially were banned from declaring their party affiliations in the election, those of <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Muslim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> campaigned openly. The deafeat led to a series of firings and resignations within the PPP. In December, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> was back in the limelight with her much-publicized marriage, arranged in the Islamic tradition, to a <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION> businessman. This year she has been making a series of barnstorming trips into the Pakistani hinterlands. She also has managed to rally her party around a new cause: the fate of about 400 Pakistanis still in prison for violations of martial law in 1977-85. Although Prime Minister <PERSON> Junejo </PERSON> has promised to review some of the cases, a constitutional amendment at the time of the restoration of civilian rule blocks the judicial review of decisions made during martial law. End Adv Wed PMs April 13
