<SECOND>PM-US-International Pay,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Cheapest, Norway Most Expensive for US Employers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> was the cheapest country last year and <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> the most expensive for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employers who measure labor costs in dollars, according to figures compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. In dollar terms, costs in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> were $ 1.37 an hour in 1987, compared with $ 1.49 in 1986 and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> average of $ 13.46. Wages more than doubled when measured in Mexican pesos, but the peso's foreign exchange value fell so quickly that labor costs in dollars actually declined <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s average hourly compensation totaled 118.52 kroner, or about $ 17.58. The figures released Monday take into account of the drop in the value of the dollar, changes in local pay rates, the cost of social insurance and other benefits. The calculations do not include the relative efficiency of workers in different countries. Wages and other benefits for workers rose in terms of Brazilian cruzados, but in dollar terms there was a decline to $ 1.49 from $ 1.60 an hour because of the low value of the cruzado against the dollar. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> are the Third World's two biggest debtors, which tends to depress the foreign exchange value of their currencies. They were the only two nations where dollar-denominated labor costs dropped last year. Low wage rates in developing countries are considered a key competitive advantage for those nations in exporting goods to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Labor in the newly-industrialized countries of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> remained less than a fifth as costly as in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Costs in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s `` four tigers'' _ <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> _ rose by only 1 to 4 percentage points relative to those in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Of 22 countries, eight had costs higher than the $ 13.46 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> hourly average. They were, in addition to <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>: <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, 25.46 Swiss francs, or $ 17.06; <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 30.26 marks, or $ 16.83; <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, 96.07 krona, or $ 15.14; <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, 30.61 guilders, or $ 15.11; <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, 563.37 Belgian francs, or $ 15.08 and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, 99.20 kroner, or $ l4 .49 All 23 countries for which the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had statistics, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, showed higher labor costs in terms of their own currency. `` <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s relative cost level in 1987 _ of 84 percent _ greatly exceeded the previous peak of 72 percent reached in 1986,'' said the report from the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>. The increase in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s labor costs was due largely to the rise of the yen against the dollar. That also was the reason for most of the rise in European costs, although they also were affected by declines in working hours by <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, the report stated.
</TEXT>
