<HEAD>University Setting Up International Computer Bank Of Products</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American companies soon will have access to a new computer database offering information about millions of products made by their foreign competitors, according to the head of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> project. `` It is the only one of its kind in the country,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulds </PERSON>, assistant professor of international marketing, said Monday. `` It's kind of surprising given the emphasis on product quality now. The International Product Quality Database uses various consumer reports to come up with product quality rankings from on an item and on up to 48 specific product features, said <PERSON> Faulds </PERSON>. It also has marketing information on the products, he said. `` We're still compiling -LRB- entries -RRB- and trying to develop off-campus computer capability ... so <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies can tap into this by phone,'' <PERSON> Faulds </PERSON> said. <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Neel </PERSON>, dean of the university's College of Business where the database was created, said the computer bank would give <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers an edge in knowing the strengths and weaknesses of their international competition, thereby helping them improve their own positions in the marketplace. So far, the database has nearly a million brand names and rankings on products sold in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> The </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Faulds </PERSON> said the database should be available to American companies in less than two years, but the university had not decided whether to let foreign businesses have access. `` We're kind of debating that right now,'' he said. `` There is a political side.'' <PERSON> Faulds </PERSON> said he has spent five years collecting the product quality rankings and comments by such groups as automobile testers, government bureaus, engineering associations, independent and consumer product testing groups.
