dios </ORGANIZATION>, then sold them in 1986 to media entrepreneur <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> for $ 1.5 billion plus assumption of some of its debt. As part of that deal, <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON> immediately bought back the <LOCATION> UA </LOCATION> segment. Later, <PERSON> Turner </PERSON> sold off all of the <ORGANIZATION> MGM </ORGANIZATION> unit, except its film library, which he retained for use on his Atlanta-based superstation <ORGANIZATION> WTBS </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON> purchased the studio and <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telepictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> bought some other assets. <PERSON> Kerkorian </PERSON> paid a total of $ 730 million to buy back the two segments. The new <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> has had spotty success. Its recent film `` Moonstruck'' is a box-office hit and has been nominated for six Academy Awards. Its new film, `` Bright Lights, <LOCATION> Big </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>,'' starring <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, ranked third in box-office gross for its debut weekend. Ticket sales still were being tallied. Last year, the company scored a hit with the <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> thriller `` The Living Daylights.'' But <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> also has had box-office flops, including its critically acclaimed but poorly attended `` Masquerade,'' as well as `` Fatal Beauty,'' `` Real Men,'' and `` Dead of Winter.'' For its first quarter ended Nov. 30, earnings dropped 19 percent to $ 2.1 million from $ 2.6 million, although revenue rose 39 percent to $ 182 million from $ 131 million. The company cited continuing high start-up costs as well as an unspecified writedown on the film `` Real Men.'' For its first fiscal year ended Aug. 31, the company lost $ 88.1 million on revenue of $ 427.6 million. <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, who has been seeking to get back into