<FIRST>r f PM-ImportStudy     04-05 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Import Study,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Import Automakers' Study Refutes Big Three Dumping Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> auto importers have issued a study attempting to refute a Big Three review that found Japanese automakers were dumping compact pickup trucks on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market. The importers' study found Japanese automakers continued earning profits averaging $ 1,000 per vehicle sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> compared with the $ 100 - $ 125 profit on each vehicle they sold in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> Japanese companies were earning an average $ 2,000 per vehicle sold here when the yen began appreciating against the dollar in 1985, leaving a cushion that let them raise prices by less than the yen had appreciated while preserving profits, the study indicated. The study was prepared by <ORGANIZATION> ICF </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Fairfax </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, research firm, for <ORGANIZATION> Automobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Importers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in anticipation of a <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vehicle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> study released last week. The import association's members include <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Isuzu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Suzuki </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> The <ORGANIZATION> MVMA </ORGANIZATION> study, prepared on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, was conducted by a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> law firm and found that Japanese makers were charging 10 percent to 48 percent less at the factory for small pickups destined for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market than for the same vehicles destined for their home market. The <ORGANIZATION> MVMA </ORGANIZATION> study also argued that the Big Three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers were being injured by the dumping because they were not able to make full use of factories and Japanese undercutting had hurt their profits. The importers' study looked mostly at cars because of the strength of the domestic truck market, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>, the analyst who prepared it, said Monday. `` One reason we were n't concerned about doing a dumping calculation on trucks was because the -LRB- domestics makers' -RRB- market performance was so strong in terms of growth in sales and growth in market share,'' <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said. In 1987, sales of small pickups by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> grew by about 10 percent, or 135,000 trucks, while Japanese makers' sales fell by about the same in a steady market, he said. Truck buyers are motivated strongly by price, <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said, so if the Japanese makers were pricing unfairly low they would have held or gained sales. The study, completed March 14, also indicated: _ About 25 percent of Japanese makers' costs, including advertising, marketing, distribution and freight, are incurred in dollars and are not affected by the currency's weakness against the yen _ Japanese companies have countered some of the pressures of the strong yen by improving productivity and transferring parts production from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> to lower-cost countries such as <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry charging foreign competitors with dumping, or selling products in this market for less than in their home market or for less than the cost of production, must prove it has been harmed by the practice before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government will impose punitive import duties. In the study, <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> stated domestic makers held their share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car and truck market in 1987 despite a 1 million-vehicle drop in their sales and a 1.15 million-vehicle overall drop in the market. Much of the decline was borne by <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, whose share of the domestic market fell nearly five percentage points in 1987 as its lost sales to domestic competitors rather than to foreign makers, the study found.
