<HEAD>Dollar Rises; Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar rose against most major currencies in quiet early trading in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> today when markets reopened after a four-day shutdown in most centers for the long Easter holiday weekend. Gold prices were mixed after the holiday break. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.58 yen to close at 124.43 yen, compared with 123.85 on Monday. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 124.52 yen. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound, which hit a six-year high of $ 1.8895 for two straight days last Thursday and Friday, eased to $ 1.888. However, many dealers expected sterling to push ahead later in the week. One <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> dealer said general market sentiment toward the dollar appeared cool, despite the rises in early trading. `` Few people want to give dollars at this level,'' said the dealer. `` They are keeping an eye on the central banks and are holding back. No sudden fall, but the dollar may drift slowly lower.'' Other dollar rates at mid-morning today, compared with late Friday's quotes, included: 1.6585 West German marks, up from 1.6565; 1.3658 Swiss francs, up from 1.3635; 5.6225 French francs, down from 5.6270; 1.8615 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8595; 1,230.20 Italian lire, up from 1,228.75; and 1.2415 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2335. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 455.75 a troy ounce, compared with late Thursday's $ 454.50. At mid-morning Tuesday, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 456. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the noon bid price was $ 455.75, down from $ 457.50 late Thursday. Bullion dealers said trading was quiet with no new direction following the Easter holiday. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold markets were closed because of a public holiday. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.78 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $ 6.72.
