<HEAD>Trade Journal: Japanese Imports Below Quota for '87 Fiscal Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese automakers will fall short of their quota for car exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the fiscal year ended March 31, an industry trade journal says. Lagging sales by <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> will account for most of the shortfall, Automotive News predicted Monday The Japanese government limits its automakers' car exports to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> to 2.3 million a year. Automotive News predicted that a final tally of shipments will indicate a shortfall of 70,000 to 100,000 cars. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> shipped about 475,544 cars to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for the 1987 fiscal year, about 66,200 below its allocation from the Japanese government, <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> said, citing high inventories and slow sales of <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> cars here. The Japanese government divides the total quota among exporting automakers, preventing companies that use their full allocation from shipping additional cars to take up the slack left by companies with slow sales. <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION>'s 1987 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> import sales were off 17.2 percent from 1986 and had dropped a further 32.2 percent in 1988 as of February. Analysts have said <ORGANIZATION> Nissan </ORGANIZATION> sales have slipped recently because the automaker has introduced relatively few new products. Automotive News said <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Toyota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANI