<HEAD>Japanese Auto Plants in US Could Cost 45,000 Jobs, GAO Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT to worst-case sted worse; picks up
3rd graf pvs bg'ng, The GAO ...; SUBS 9th graf to make same change;
picks up 10th graf pvs bg'ng, At a ...; Also moved on general
newswires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The seven Japanese automakers' plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> may cause 45,000 jobs to be lost in the domestic industry, far fewer than the number estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, a government study says. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> study said that its estimate for job losses from 1985 through 1990 was based on worst-case assumptions, and the number of jobs actually lost could be less. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study, requested by Reps. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., <PERSON> Marcy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaptur </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON>, R-Ill., placed the job loss at slightly less than a quarter the 200,000 lost jobs expected by the Imports, increased productivity and use of foreign parts will shrink the number of auto-industry jobs by 1990, according to the study, released Monday. `` The operations of Japanese-affiliated automakers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could result in even more losses because they use fewer workers and more foreign content than <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automakers,'' the study said. Japanese auto plants in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> were established in part to forestall protectionist legislation in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> by giving <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> workers a chance to work in Japanese assembly plants. Japanese automakers have invested more than $ 5 billion in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assembly plants since 1980. Besides the seven Japanese auto manufacturers, more than 100 Japanese auto parts suppliers operate in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> estimate was based on what the study called unprovable assumptions about the extent to which U.S.-made Japanese autos cut into domestic manufacturing rather than displace imports. The worst-case estimate assumed 85 percent of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production displaced production by the domestic automakers, a level the agency called `` relatively high.'' At a 70 percent displacement rate, the job loss shrinks to 17,000, and from 60 percent down the Japanese production creates more jobs than it eliminates, the study said. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study also assumed half the Japanese makers' parts would be bought in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production by Japanese makers would total 1.8 million vehicles in 1990. The <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> study produced a higher job-loss estimate because it assumed the Japanese manufacturers would build 2.2 million vehicles in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, all of which would cut into domestic production, and would buy only 30 percent of their parts in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
