<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Light </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> must deliver electricity generated by the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Buckeye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> cooperative to the city of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marys </ORGANIZATION>, a federal appeals court ruled today. A three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in favor of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marys </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Buckeye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> and the affiliated <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power-Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> electricity cooperative in a 7-year-old dispute with <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Light. The appeals court's unanimous decision upholds a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ruling that <ORGANIZATION> DP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L is bound by terms of a 1968 contract to deliver the <LOCATION> Buckeye </LOCATION> Power-generated electricity over <ORGANIZATION> DP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L's power network to the city of St. Marys. <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Light had disagreed and appealed the commission's ruling. The appeals court said a Jan. 1, 1968, contract between <ORGANIZATION> Buckeye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> and six investor-owned utilities, including <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Light, requires <ORGANIZATION> DP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L to `` wheel' the power over its lines from the <LOCATION> Buckeye </LOCATION> cooperative to <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marys </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> DP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L lawyers argued that the company did not intend, under terms of the 1968 contract, to deliver such power. <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marys </ORGANIZATION> operates a municipal electric utility and buys electric power from both DP & amp; L and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power-Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> corporation which buys electricity from <ORGANIZATION> Buckeye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> members for resale to AMP-Ohio member municipal utilities. <ORGANIZATION> Buckeye </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> generates and transmits electricity for 29 member systems that constitute all of the electric cooperatives selling power in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. The dispute dates to April 1981.
