<HEAD>Tandy's Moves Into Big Markets Hampered By Image, Network Systems</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALT SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s success in retailing home computers is not carrying over easily into the big-business market. The parent company of the <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shack </ORGANIZATION> chain of electronics stores announced its big push into the Fortune 1000 last August and has relatively little to show for it so far. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> are the only big customers that have so far allowed <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> to mention them by name. The Radio Shack name, a magnet in shopping malls, does not impress people who run corporate data centers. And some analysts believe the company lacks the technical and sales savvy to make it against industry giants like <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> has about 8 percent of the overall <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> computer market, but only 2 to 3 percent of the Fortune 1000, according to <ORGANIZATION> Future </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a Dallas-based market researcher `` The old Radio Shack quality issue still hurts them,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Forrester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cambridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION>. `` It's one thing to buy a tape deck that does n't work, but it's another thing to have the computer that you're running your company on break down.'' The knock on quality may be unjustified, based on independent evaluations. But Tandy still strikes some corporate buyers as a company for electronics hobbyists. Computers made up only about 30 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>'s business last year, outweighed by its sales of electronic parts and equipment, radios, telephones, video equipment, tape recorders, toys and communication equipment. Playing to its strengths, <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> continues to focus most of its efforts on selling to small - and medium-sized companies, <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Juge </PERSON>, the director of market planning, said in a recent interview `` We have not claimed to have made large inroads into the big corporate market. What we have said is that our level of penetration is much greater,'' <PERSON> Juge </PERSON> said. `` It's never been our intention to unseat <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Juge </PERSON> said members of the sales force are told that for every call they make on a Fortune 1000 company, they should be making about 70 calls to smaller companies. <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>'s push to move in on <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s established big-business market began in August 1987. It centered on creating <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> computer centers separate from the Radio Shack stores, spending $ 80 million to refurbish many of the 8,500 outlets and improving training for sales people. That sales force has encountered some resistance, but most companies are willing to try <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>'s systems, said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>'s business products division. `` It has n't proven too difficult to have most of them take a unit for evaluation,'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. `` If we can get them to compare our systems with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s, we compare very favorably.'' Some analysts say there is a perception in corporate <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> that <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> lacks equipment to connect its computers to each other. `` In the very large corporate market, connectivity becomes a very large issue,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Cross </PERSON>, an analyst with Future Computing. `` When you think of networking or office integration, <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> is not the first name that pops to mind.'' Last month <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> announced plans to license its DeskMate interface to software developers, hoping to establish the look and feel of its personal computer screen as an industry standard. It said its computers can be easily hooked together in networks. But <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Glazer </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, said he thinks <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>'s problem has more to do with marketing than technology. `` Everything that's available in networking, <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> has access to. <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> has systems as good as any out there, but it needs to convince the large companies that it has quality products to offer,'' he said. `` Selling connected solutions in the next couple of years will be our thrust,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Roach </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, noting the company's sales force has been successful in other areas. Sales at recently refurbished stores have risen about 4 percent faster than sales at stores that have not been refurbished, the company reported. Overall Tandy sales, meanwhile, improved to $ 3.66 billion in calendar year 1987, compared with $ 3.32 billion in 1986, and net income in 1987 improved to $ 289.8 million, compared with $ 216.4 million in 1986. Company executives also believe Fortune 500 companies, concerned about quality and value, will look at <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> products on an equal footing with other computer systems. `` The problem is simply one of penetration and presence,'' Future Computing's Cross said. `` <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>, when it came out with a personal computer, already had contacts with every company in the country with its mainframes.'' Industry rumors have it that <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> plans this month to unveil the first computer compatible with <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION>'s Personal System-2 computer, which was introduced in April 1987. Juge wo n't confirm or deny the rumor. The company has called a news conference for April 21 to introduce two products _ one a computer product and the other, `` an invention that will have impact on multiple areas in the electronics field.'' <PERSON> Roach </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> waited to introduce high-end personal computers rather than put an inferior product on the market. `` We have a very broad-based distribution network and many repeat customers,'' he said. `` Often we will elect not to carry a product because we feel like some percentage of the market will not be happy with it.'' <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> also has begun fighting for a share of the market in portable laptop computers that can perform many of the same functions as an IBM-compatible desk unit. To help the company compete in the tough laptop market, <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION> recently purchased <ORGANIZATION> Grid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, for $ 55 million. Grid, which designs, manufactures and markets rugged, magnesium-cased portable microcomputers, will become a wholly owned subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Tandy </ORGANIZATION>.
