<NOTE>For Release Monday April 11 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>New Orleans Is Popping With Shopping Malls, Despite Oil Bust</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY FOSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Boom times went bust here in the 1980s, yet glitzy, upscale shopping malls keep popping up along the <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, in the suburbs and in the shadow of the <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Superdome. Some might say it's crazy to build retail developments in a city going through a slump often compared to the Great Depression. But <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> says its good business. <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> is the regional development director for the <ORGANIZATION> Edward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> J. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> DeBartolo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which is building the 8,000-square-foot, $ 100 million complex that will open next to the Superdome in August. It will compete for attention with the new Galleria in suburban <LOCATION> Metairie </LOCATION>, the year-old Riverwalk on the riverside site of the 1984 world's fair, Canal Place at the foot of the city's major thoroughfare and at least five other shopping developments that have been constructed or expanded in the area since 1980. <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> said the failure of the oil economy in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, which hit just as <PERSON> DeBartolo </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Centre </LOCATION> was being planned, did not give his company second thoughts about the project. `` Frankly this has seemed like a very solid idea all along. We have a great location, and we're bringing in <ORGANIZATION> Macy </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lord </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, two stores that people from this area have always traveled to other cities to shop in,'' <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> said. For years, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> residents planned trips to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, and other cities to shop, according to <PERSON> Stella </PERSON> <PERSON> Schramm </PERSON>, the director of the <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>'s economic development department. `` <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> was grossly under-retailed in the past,'' she explained. `` In 1980, our per-capita income surpassed the national average. That sent up a red flag that got a lot of attention from national retailers who had previously ignored <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>.'' As retailers began to plan and build new shopping facilities in the area, however, the oil-based economy began to falter. The price of oil plummeted, oil-related businesses failed, and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>'s unemployment rate soared above 14 percent In 1985, when the first phase of the Esplanade Mall opened, the economy was still in good shape. But by the time the second phase opened in 1986, mall general manager <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Grondin </PERSON> said things had changed radically. `` I wondered for a while if I'd be looking for another job myself,'' he said. `` We had a slow period, which is normal for a new mall, but I was reading all the negative economic news in the papers at that time, and I was worried.'' Mall managers and developers remain resolutely confident, however. While the local economy is still slow, most feel there are definite signs of recovery. `` The important thing about economic forecasts,'' <PERSON> Schramm </PERSON> said, `` is expectation. Expectation was very bad while oil prices were fluctuating. Now that they're fairly stable, even though they're not as high as people would like, things are improving. Another factor that's helping the local economy is tourism, and for the new shopping centers in the area, that's a two-way street. `` Definitely. We see people making trips here just to shop,'' <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> <PERSON> Gianna </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We also see the effect of the new shopping opportunities on our convention trade. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> is now No. 1 for spouse attendance at conventions in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. I'm sure having all these great stores is one reason for that.'' <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON> agrees, saying now that national merchants are opening here, local folks are shopping at home, and tourists are in those same stores. `` That's not only keeping that money in the local economy, it's bringing it into the city from other areas Let's face it, if you live in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, or <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and you have a chance to go to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> for a weekend of shopping, it's an easy choice. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> can now offer both the French Quarter and the stores people want. Where do you think people are going to be going?''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday April 11</NOTE>
