orted in the company's 10K report with the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> last week that it expects a $ 43 million loss by the time the reorganization plan is completed. The expected loss in 1988 represents a continuing deterioration of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION>'s loan portfolio, plus operating losses and non-recurring charges related to the federally assisted rescue plan. In the first quarter of 1987, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> recorded a loss of $ 44.5 million, and it lost $ 232.4 million during the same quarter in 1986. For all of 1987, the company posted a loss of $ 1.13 billion, compared to a loss of $ 402 million in 1986. <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> had forecast a $ 1.1 billion loss for 1987, based on an expected $ 852 million fourth-quarter deficit. But the company's fourth-quarter loss rose to $ 861 million <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, with 59 banks in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and one in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, grew quickly during the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil boom, but was hammered by energy and real estate losses when oil prices plummeted. For 1987, the company posted a $ 1.1 billion loss. The bailout plan for <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' fourth-largest bank-holding company calls for $ 970 million in assistance from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 500 million infusion of capital raised privately by a group headed by <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>, who would become chairman under the plan, and a spinoff of $ 1.79 billion in book value of poorly performing assets. First City extended its deadline for the tender offer until April 12 after only 62 percent, or $ 140 million, of the bank's $ 225.8 million in bonds had been tendered by March 29 Under the arrangement, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> debt holders have been offered 45 cents on the dollar for their debt, while subordinated debt holders have been offered 35 cents.
