<FILEID>AP-NR-04-05-88 1503EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-JobHunting Bjt   04-05 0533</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Job Hunting, Bjt,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Placement Pro Says It's a Tough Year for College Grads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New college graduates this spring will face a tight job market, with competition-conscious companies less willing to offer extended on-the-job training, a veteran placement professional says. `` Employers, especially small - and medium-size companies which represent the areas of greatest job growth, today have neither the time nor inclination to ` bring somebody along' gradually,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Challenger </PERSON>, president of Chicago-based Challenger, <ORGANIZATION> Gray </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Christmas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which descibes itself as the nation's oldest outplacement firm `` Now, you either sink or swim, right away.'' An increasingly competitive marketplace is facing all companies, <PERSON> Challenger </PERSON> said in an analysis of the 1988 college graduate job outlook, released Monday. `` As a result, many of the larger firms have instituted corporate downsizing to pare their overhead and operating expenses, which has not only eliminated or combined many existing jobs but also prevented the creation of many new entry-level jobs. `` The two-year training programs for beginners are among casualties of world market competition,'' he said. `` Companies want results now, not in two years.'' Challenger, 62, founded his firm in 1962 and says it has helped more than 20,000 people who have lost jobs find employment. The firm has 14 regional offices in cities including <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION>. Challenger said the job market wo n't favor most graduates because companies are more selective. He said early indications suggest that fewer than the usual one-third of students getting four-year degrees will have jobs lined up when they receive diplomas. College placement officials say that just 20 percent to 25 percent of students graduating have jobs set, but things could change by the end of May, Challenger said in a telephone interview. The graduates likely to have the most luck finding positions are `` the A students and those with specialty degrees such as engineering or accounting,'' or those going into sales, Challenger said. `` Companies are always willing to take on sales trainees'' because many sales jobs are low-salary or operate on commission, he said. Some students are taking unpaid internships to obtain good jobs, Challenger said. Others may have to take part-time work as they search for permanent positions. Some placement experts disagree with Challenger's assessment. <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lindquist </PERSON>, director of placement for <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Evanston </LOCATION>, said his survey of employers indicates a better employment year spring graduates. He said in a telephone interview Tuesday that the university's survey last fall forecast a 10 percent increase in new-graduate employment over the previous year <PERSON> Lindquist </PERSON> agreed that takeovers and corporate restructurings have heightened competition for new jobs. `` If you were making $ 35,000 and you're offered $ 30,000 you might not like it, but it's better than unemployment,'' said <PERSON> Lindquist </PERSON>. But at the same time, he said, many companies `` are very, very heavily in the market -LRB- for new employees -RRB- and have made a big commitment to training. `` Not having a job by commencement is not necessarily the end of the world,'' <PERSON> Lindquist </PERSON> said. `` There'll be more kids hired in June, July, August and September than there probably were in the previous four months. And there's nothing at all unusual about that.''
</TEXT>
