<HEAD>Dollar Strengthens; Gold Falls</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar surged higher against major foreign currencies Tuesday as traders decided Japanese investors were unlikely to unload dollars. Gold prices fell. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> said gold was bid at $ 452.65 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $ 455.85 late Monday. The dollar climbed about 1 percent against the West German mark, British pound and Japanese yen. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency's strength prompted people who had been betting on a dollar decline to retreat by buying dollars to cover short positions. That contributed to the dollar's rally. The dollar had been depressed in March by fears that Japanese trust funds and securities firms would lighten their dollar holdings starting April 1 because they would no longer need to support it for accounting purposes. When Japanese dollar-selling failed to materialize, investors took courage, said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Spence </PERSON>, vice president of foreign exchange at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. Dollar buyers were also encouraged by news reports that <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Governor <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Angell </PERSON> expressed a strong desire to lower inflation, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gloyne </PERSON>, senior trader at <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION>. If the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> tried to combat inflation through higher interest rates, it would raise the yield of dollar-denominated securities and make foreigners want to buy dollars. Interest rates finished Tuesday little changed. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose 0.58 yen to a close at 124.43 yen, compared with 123.85 on Monday. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 125.15 yen. At the end of the trading day in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 125.28 yen, up from 124.18 yen late Monday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell to $ 1.8800 from $ 1.8895 on Good Friday. Later in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the pound fell to $ 1.8790 from $ 1.8857 late Monday. There was spotty foreign-exchange trading in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> on Friday but no precious metals trading. The European financial markets were closed on Monday for the Easter holiday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with Monday's rates, were: 1.6706 West German marks, up from 1.6540; 1.3769 Swiss francs, up from 1.3639; 1.2418 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2370; 5.6645 French francs, up from 5.6085; and 1,237.75 Italian lire, up from 1,227.25 Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with Friday's rates: 1.6690 West German marks, up from 1.6565; 1.3765 Swiss francs, up from 1.3635; 5.6605 French francs, up from 5.6270; 1.8700 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8595; 1,234.50 Italian lire, up from 1,228.75; 1.2395 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2335. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold bullion for current delivery was bid at $ 453.40 a troy ounce, down from $ 456.70 late Monday. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 451.50 a troy ounce, compared with late Thursday's $ 454.50. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold fell, closing at a bid $ 453.50 an ounce compared with $ 457.50 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold markets were closed because of a public holiday. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery was bid at $ 6.65 an ounce, down from $ 6.789 an ounce late Monday. Silver bullion prices fell on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market, where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.65 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $ 6.72.
