<FIRST>u f AM-AirFares Bjt   04-05 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Air Fares, Bjt,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern, Continental Cut Some Air Fares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Two units of fare-wars veteran <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> fired a spring salvo Tuesday by announcing price cuts on tickets purchased by April 14. The subsidiaries, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, may touch off a price skirmish only a few weeks after all the major carriers hiked fares steeply. But the cuts _ limited by the purchase-period requirements and hemmed in by other restrictions _ stop short of a full-fledged price war. Although observers believe the reductions made by Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> are likely to be matched by other major airlines, they do n't see a major fare battle on the horizon. `` It's definitely not a fare war; it's barely a skirmish,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Starkman </PERSON>, an airline analyst for investment firm <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. If anything, the current climate for the industry appears to favor fare hikes rather than reductions. The major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carriers have posted an average increase in passenger traffic of 7 percent to 8 percent since New Year's Day from the same period last year. The robust demand prompted the big airlines to raise their first-class, economy and discount fares in mid-March by 15 percent to 85 percent, depending on the destination. The carriers also tightened restrictions on their popular `` MaxSaver'' discount fares, the cheapest available. The big fare hikes came several weeks before they normally do, as the airlines jumped the gun on the peak travel season that starts in April. Eastern and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's sixth-largest and fifth-ranked airlines, respectively, said Tuesday they were cutting some fares in anticipation of a slack period coming up for leisure travel. `` The period between Easter and the start of summer vacations in mid-June is always a slack travel time, and an early Easter extends the off-peak period this year,'' said <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, vice president of marketing communications for Eastern. `` We hope to give leisure travel a boost with fares so low that people will take a trip they might not otherwise plan.'' With the new fares, the airline said, passengers will be able to fly midweek to more than 80 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cities on Eastern for a maximum of $ 99 one way -LRB- based on a round-trip tariff of $ 198 -RRB-. Eastern's round-trip fare between <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, for example, will fall to $ 178 under the program, compared with the current `` MaxSaver'' fare of $ 208 Although there are some minor differences, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> introduced similar programs. The non-refundable tickets must be purchased by April 14 -LRB- starting Tuesday for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and Wednesday for <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, and used for travel from April 18 through June 15. Passengers must travel between noon Monday and noon Thursday. Round-trip travel and a Saturday night stay are required. Those restrictions limit the program to eight travel days in April, 18 days in May and nine in June. And there are still more restrictions. For Eastern, tickets must be bought within 24 hours after making reservations. Continental is even stricter: It requires reservations and ticketing to be done at the same time. Both airlines prohibit schedule changes to be made the special fares and limit the number of available seats on each flight. `` It's pretty savvy of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Geller </PERSON>, a transportation analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Provident </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. `` It very effectively cancels out every businessperson'' from using the new fares. <PERSON> Geller </PERSON> suggested that the reduced tariffs could encourage people who had planned vacations to take them within the specified time frames.
</TEXT>
