<HEAD>Saudi Arabian Oil Minister to Visit Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s oil minister will visit <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> this week to discuss the international market situation, the government announced Tuesday. A statement from the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the visit of <PERSON> Hisham </PERSON> <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> `` responds to the traditional and active Mexican policy of dialogue and cooperation with other producing nations of petroleum, members or not members of <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION>, as well as with consuming nations.'' It said such communication `` has the purpose of reconciling national interests with the development of a stable internaitonal market with profitable prices, that might allow a more predictable and consistent evolution of the international market situation.'' The statement said <PERSON> Nazer </PERSON> would arrive Wednesday and meet Thursday with President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON> after first holding discussions with <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mines </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiriart </PERSON> and with <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Rojas </PERSON>, director of the state oil monopoly <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> is not a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> but closely monitors its price and production guidelines. It was the world's fourth largest oil producer in 1985 but since has slipped to sixth place behind the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. On Monday night, <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> announced that it lowered the price of its light Isthums crude by $ 1.62 a barrel to Japanese customers in March. <ORGANIZATION> Pemex </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the price of the light oil was $ 13.86 a barrel in March, down from $ 15.48 a barrel in February. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> buys 180,000 barrels a day of crude, accounting for 11 percent of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s total oil exports in March.
